Starting around 10:00 pm, I began to experience chills and shivering, despite being under covers/in bed. By about 11:00 pm, I was starting to feel nauseous and panicked -- racing thoughts, rapid heartbeat. I have experienced panic attacks before, so I thought that it could be the start of a panic attack. By 11:30 pm, I vomited about 1 L of fluids/bile/etc. My fever reached 101.0 at that point. I didn't vomit anymore throughout the night but remained nauseous. At 8 am the next day (4/7/21), my fever was at 100.9.  I was still nauseous and had a headache, so I drank Gatorade and an Alka Seltzer. I slept for most of the day. By 5:00 pm on 4/7/21, my fever was down to 99.5. I was able to eat toast and continue drinking water and Gatorade. It has now been 48 hours since the vaccine and as of 9:00 am on 4/8/21, I feel 100% back to normal, other than continued soreness at the injection site.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient presented himself for COVID19 Vaccine administration on 04/05/2021 at 4:10pm. Upon checking in for his appointment, he was provided with Conviva?s COVID19 vaccine screening and consent form in which he denied the following:  ? Having allergies and reactions to any medication, foods, vaccines, or latex.  ? Carrying an Epi-pen for emergency treatment of anaphylaxis.  ? Having had a severe reaction to previous dose of this vaccine or to any of the ingredients of this vaccine.  After the vaccine administration, patient was guided to the observation area for a 15-minute observatory period.  At approximately 4:25 pm- patient, while in the observation area, expressed to the clinical staff member monitoring the area, that he felt lightheaded and needed to lay down, he leaned forward, and the clinical alert team was activated.  Patient was lowered to the floor; a pillow was placed under his head and his feet were elevated.  Vitals reported were taken in the presence of registered nurse while patient was laying on the floor.  Vitals ? Glucose 97 ? Blood pressure 120/77 ? Oxygen saturation level 97% ? Pulse 72 Register nurse reports that patient was laying on the floor, alert, oriented to place, time and person. Patient never lost consciousness and within approximately 5-7 minutes he was sitting up, drinking water. At this time, patient was asked the following series of questions: ? How do you feel? As per patient, he was feeling nauseous, dizzy, and anxious.  ? Are you allergic to any medications or have you had any allergic reactions to a vaccine? Patient denied having had a history of any adverse or allergic reaction to any medication or vaccines in the past.  Several minutes later patient stated that he was feeling better and he was assisted to sit up. Patient stated that he was feeling fine, and able to drive. Patient was kept in the observation area an additional 15 minutes.   At approximately 4:40 pm- After patient was considered stable by doctor, he was checked out. Patient was given phone numbers in case he had any clinical or general questions.   At 6:00 pm- (Center Administration) called patient, he stated that he was still driving and felt fine.  At 6:21 pm- Patient sent a text to Center Administrator, stating the had arrived home and was feeling fine.

Noted change of consciousness in evening following vaccination.  She had a tonic gaze to the right when EMS 1st arrived at the scene.  She was not having any overt epileptic activity. She is normally very debilitated and moderately demented but conversational and jovial according to the daughter.  She is normally able to be fed, taken to the toilet, and has no trouble with day-to-day living.  She was brought to this hospital day after vaccination.  She was alert at the time of the vaccination.  She had COVID in August of this last year.  In ED, she was given a very small dose of Ativan.  She had immediate effect from this with resolution of the tonic gaze, developed a voluntary gaze and had minimal but clear-cut purposeful conversation.  She was also able to move her extremities after the Ativan.  Prior to that she was fairly rigid in her extremities.  She did not have any obvious seizure activity however.  She was transferred to another hospital for higher level of care and continued management.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the evening of March 31, 2021, itching was noticed at the injection site. Prior to this, no side effects after the March 23, 2021, injection had been observed. By the morning of April 1, 2021, a red, raised, itchy rash was noticeable at the injection site that was warm/hot to the touch. The rash continued to spread through April 6, 2021, running from about 4 cm above the elbow to the shoulder and encompassing most of the "injection side" of the arm. An ice gel bead pack was applied to the rash area multiple times per day April 1-April 6, 2021. The arm ached shoulder to hand on April 5, 2021. That evening, two ibuprofen caplets (400 mg total) were taken, followed up with the same dose both the morning and evening of April 6, 2021. The rash faded as quickly as it appeared starting the morning of April 7, 2021. As of the submission of this report, very mild itching is still present but the rash has faded almost entirely and can only be seen at the margins if you know where to look.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within one minute of receiving the shot I felt disoriented and had trouble determining if I had buttoned my shirt correctly. For the next two and half hours I had trouble recalling basic things that I should have been observing such as which highway my driver had taken me home on although I knew where I was at.   I also experienced irregular breathing. To be specific, I would take a very large breath, a very short breath, or miss a breath. This started as a series of one to three irregular breaths every five minutes or so. My breaths became more irregular in the next hour. While driving to my employers office about fifteen or twenty minutes after my shot, my right eye closed and I could not open it for about seven seconds. My breathing also became deep and the pace was not under my control. Once at the office I sat in my manager's office to be observed. I experienced more intense episodes of the above listed symptoms such as both eyes closing and the left one watering. The watering continued into the next day periodically. At least two times while my eyes closed I had to put my elbow on the desk and my hand on my head to make sure I didn't fall out of the chair. I also felt very uncomfortable causing me to moan. This happened one time.   After this my manager called my parents and they came to take me home. It took them one hour to get there. While waiting I felt light headed and the breathing irregularities became less intense. When they got there I mainly felt disoriented. The disorientation could be best described as slightly impaired or slowed decision making.   I would also like to know if I should receive the second vaccination.
LAB_DATA: I did not contact any medical workers about this incident.
ALLERGIES: None that I am aware of.

Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I noticed raised itchy bumps and redness on my left arm at injection site the morning after my shot, they could have been shortly after I was vaccinated, but I was really only looking for any issues that might be life threatening. Over the following two weeks, the bumps/itchiness worsened and spread across all of my body except at my hands, feet, face, and lower back. Nearing the end of the second week, as the conditions worsened my skin felt painful all over (like a very bad sun burn). Due to the discomfort, I was largely unable to sleep during this period and had difficulty focusing on work. At week one I started taking Benadryl and applying lotion on my skin. I informed my PCP as well as the clinic that administered the vaccine of my condition. The clinic said they could do nothing unless my condition was life threatening. My PCP advised that an itchy rash is a rare side effect of the vaccine but that it would get better typically within 8-12 days. He also advised on taking an additional over the counter antihistamine along with the Benadryl, which I did.  None of the antihistamines made the conditions better, they continued to worsen. I started taking Ibuprofen for the discomfort and pain. By the end of the second week, my rash became more painful especially at my chest, neck, and ears - the skin became quite red and looked a bit like a burn. At this point I did not believe I was having a safe reaction and reached out to my PCP and vaccine clinic once more.  I was not able to reach my PCP but did connect virtually with an online doctor who reviewed photos of my skin and prescribed a topical steroid. Doctor advised I see a specialist in person, with concern that taking an oral steroid might  mitigate the effects of the vaccine. I alerted the clinic that I would be seeing this specialist and they advised that I instead go to urgent care. The following day (4/6/21), I did both. Healthcare facility provided an oral steroid and did not think it would impact the vaccination. The Specialist did not want to prescribe a steroid in concern that it would mitigate the effects of the vaccine. He advised to endure the rash another 1-2 weeks. Later that night, I could not bare the pain and starting taking the oral steroid. Within 24 hours I started feeling some relief. I am on day three of six of the steroid and each day the pain, itching, and rash are getting better. I will have a meeting in person at the clinic where I received my vaccine this Friday for a doctor to assess my rash and determine if it is appropriate for me to take a second dose healthcare facility requested this meeting.
HISTORY: previous heart arrhythmia, conditions have lessened over the last 7 years (no medication required)

About 2 hours after the vaccine I started filling dizzy. It was evening, so I just went right to bed. When I woke up in the middle of the night the room was spinning. I fell back asleep, but when I woke up in the morning the room was still spinning and stayed spinning all day. I was very, very dizzy and nauseous all day (3/18). I vomited twice and struggled to keep even water down. I slept on and off all day due to fatigue and anything I tried to do made me dizzy, so sleeping was about all I could do anyway. The next day (3/19) I woke up improved, not 100%, but better. Still dizzy at times, but not as intensely and I was able to eat and drink without vomiting or nausea. For the next couple of days (3/19-3/21) the dizziness came and went, but was overall much better than 3/18. On 3/22 I woke up feeling terrible again, very, very dizzy and unwell. I was slightly nauseous from the dizziness, but was able to keep water and food down. I did a virtual appointment with a doctor, who said I had vertigo. I've had vertigo only once in my life (in January 2021), and it wasn't anything as bad as this. By 3/23 I was so miserable, I couldn't walk without assistance since I was afraid I would fall. I went in to see a doctor in person,  confirmed the vertigo diagnosis and recommended physical therapy. I did physical therapy and they said I had benign paroxysmal positional vertigo both in my left canal and in my horizontal canal. I started to slowly improve, but was unable to work due to my inability to look at a computer screen that week (3/22-3/28). I was well enough to work for 5 hours a day the week of 3/29, but unable to drive as sudden head movements continued to cause dizziness. As of 4/4 I started driving again and am feeling mostly better, but I still have dizzy spells. Dizzy spells are short and manageable. I've been very fatigued (likely from the vertigo, but who knows) since receiving the vaccine. As of today (4/8), I'm still not feeling 100%. I'm still very fatigued and still experience dizziness if I move my head too much.
OTHER_MEDS: Levothyroxine 0.100mg, taken daily Lansoprazole 15mg, taken every other day

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received covid vaccine at 12:56pm on March 31, 2021.  At 1:00pm he sat down on the floor.  He remained conscious but complained of feeling dizzy.  HR was 40. Patient's skin at 1:06pm appeared pink and WNL.  1:13pm = BP 115/75 and HR 67.  1:23pm = 130/75 HR 68.  Patient denied shortness of breath/chest pain throughout the entire episode and did not lose consciousness.  At 1:23 patient stated he no longer feels faint, just a bit weak.  At 1:24pm patient dangled on cot.  1:27pm = 130/80, HR 70.  1:33pm = left facility in the care of his mother who is driving.  He stated he feels a little weak, but not faint or dizzy.  He left ambulatory.  He refused transport or the need for additional medical care.  Follow up call was placed to pt on Friday, 4/2/21.  Pt denied any residual effects and stated he is at baseline.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Initially she passed out following the vaccine - within 90 seconds- she has a history of passing out with injections and blood draws. Around noon she had a seizure. She describes a feeling of darkness and dread closing in on her and she was unable to speak or move. She was on the stairs at the time. I witnessed her stiffen, then go limp and fall between the electric stair hair and the wall. She hit the hardwood floor face first then she began to shake/twitch. She was unconscious. She awoke screaming, incoherent speech, and flailing limbs. It took about 5 minutes to calm her and be able to understand her speech. She only remembers the darkness and waking up scared and feeling awful. She was put supine on the floor with feet elevated, blood pressure monitored, given juice to drink, and vitals checked routinely. After about an hour supine and conscious, she felt good enough to sit up. She sat up for 15 minutes before she was able to stand with assistance. Family physician was notified immediately and we are still waiting for a response. She has a goose egg sized knot on her forehead, a bruise on the side of her face and a black eye from hitting the floor. She has a huge bruise on her outer thigh and lower leg where she hit the stair chair and then seized and it it repeatedly on the metal. She has underarm pain from where her armpit hit the edge of the stairs when she fell and seized. She has no history of any types of seizures.
OTHER_MEDS: Buspar 5 mg BID Atarax 25 mg QD Loestrin
CUR_ILL: No acute illnesses - Covid mid November 2020

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Instantly felt warm and slightly dizzy as soon as the shot was administered. As the day went on, I felt very lethargic and tired. Lost strength throughout the day. Random fingers on both hands throughout the day would go numb for a few minutes at a time. In the evening, flu like symptoms set in. I felt very hot, while I was very cold. I could not sleep for longer than 2 hours at a time, despite being unbelievably tired. I got up twice during the night and vomitted. Around 3 AM, I woke up and my left arm, from my elbow down to my fingertips was completely numb. I got up and walked around, moved my arm vigorously, however, the numbness would not go away. I eventually fell back asleep after 6 AM, and woke up again around 7:20 AM. At that time, the numbness in my left arm had gone away. It was hard to get up to be active on Saturday, the day after. I spent most of the day laying down, feeling sick to my stomach, still very cold, and very tired, with no energy or strength. Around 5 PM, I started to feel better, and by 7:30 PM, I felt close to normal.   Throughout this past week, I have felt tired a majority of the time. I am sleeping 1.5-2 hours longer than I normally sleep, I lack the strength, energy, power, and endurance I had prior to the vaccine, however, that all seems to be marginally getting better each day. I am still experiencing  my fingertips on both hands going numb for short periods, from time to time, as of today, 6 days post vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine EUA. Symptoms started on Monday, 3/15, with an itch behind my knees.  On Tuesday it became a rash and progressively got worse.  That evening I had chills and fever of 102.  On Wednesday, 3/17, I went to Doctor.  She said she believed it was a reaction to the vaccine.  Rash was very itchy, painful, and red.  She said she could not give me steroid by mouth.  She prescribed Triamcinolone Acetonide ointment, .1% and told me to take Benadryl.  I did both of those things, but they did not help very much.  I also used benadryl gel.  None of those seemed to help very much.  In searching for something that would give some relief, I began applying Apple Cider Vinegar.  This helped the most.  Benadryl did help with sleep.  Rash would get hot and especially irritated at night.  It eventually spread to my upper thighs and to my right wrist.  I went back to doctor on 3/23.  I then got a cortisone shot and Rx for the same ointment .5%.  Rash continued for 2 weeks, with slowly getting better.  Took last benadryl on 3/5.

Pt was sitting at the observation area when he informed the Observer that he felt dizzy with no other symptoms. At the moment when the observer came to me, I was helping with the reconstitution of the vaccine. I literally had the vial in hand with syringe. I kindly asked her to get one of the RN's that were awaiting the arrival of pt's. She went to grab RN who then went to speak to the pt. Pt was taken to the bed we have set up here at the vaccination clinic. Pt laid  down on bed as I walked in to assist RN. I then elevated pt's legs and RN proceeded to take pt's vital signs. The ONLY symptom pt had was dizziness and a slight headache. No hives, breathing problems or swelling of the the throat. We applied a cold pack to the back of pt's neck. stayed and observed him for 15 minutes. He then stated he felt better besides the headache. No new symptoms at this point. vitals were re-taken and pt was allowed to sit up to see how he felt. Pt felt fine we then proceeded to have pt stand in which he also stated he felt fine .Pt was provided the post-vaccine handouts and verbally explained the signs and symptoms to him as well. Explained if anything severe were to happen, to call 911. Pt verbalized understanding and stated that he would. pt's wife and 2 sons were also here for a vaccine. Pts wife was instructed to drive home. No further action was required.   312pm- pt informed observer of dizziness 313pm-pt was sent to cot 315pm-BP: 158/92 HR: 69 RR: 16 O2: 98% 321pm-BP: 120/78 HR: 78 RR:20 O2: 98% T: 97F Temporal 325pm-No dizziness on cot but did complain of headache 2/10  328pm- BP: 122/78 HR:77 O2:99% T: 98F Temporal  330pm-Sat on side of bed with no dizziness 332pm-No dizziness, left facility with wife.

Despite patient having long-standing history of ET, she had a completely normal CBC in August of 2020 and was maintained on the same dose of hydrea for more than 10 years. She was found to have an abrupt drop in both hemoglobin (13->9g/dl) and platelets (300s-- >104) 2 days after her 2nd vaccine.  Her hydrea dose was lowered and repeat blood work 1 month later demonstrated platelets of 64 and hemoglobin of 6.7.  patient was admitted to the hospital and was transfused 2 units of blood.  Bone marrow biopsy demonstrated 50% cellular marrow with grade three fibrosis consistent with Post-ET MF. No evidence of hemolysis, vitamin, or iron deficiency.  Spleen not enlarged.  Hydrea was stopped completely during admission.  Today's blood work (4/8/2021) demonstrates continued thrombocytopenia and anemia - platelets of 54 and hemoglobin of 7.5.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Loud ringing in hears with muffled hearing and nausea began on approximately 2/25 (best estimate). Hearing issues progressed over the next few days to become almost constant and extremely unpleasant. Nausea became severe and turned to uncontrollable vomiting with extreme headache on Monday 2/29 and I went to Urgent care. Treatment improved headache, but did not provide complete relief. Hearing symptoms remained. Returned to Urgent care 3/1. Provided with IV steroids. Headache finally resolved. Hearing issue and mild nausea remained. By the time I obtained my second COVID vaccine (3/11) symptoms had improved by about 50%. However, after receiving second dose, they became worse again. It was then I thought of a possible connection to the vaccine. None of the doctors I had seen had brought it up and it hadn't occurred to me either. Good news for me: It has now been almost a month since my second dose and my symptoms have finally (just in the last few days) improved markedly. I still have hearing issues, mostly now just in the evenings. I am hoping this resolves soon. I am seeing an ENT and having a hearing test next week to see if there has been any damage, etc.   Given MRI. Results normal. Referred to Neurologist and ENT.
LAB_DATA: Two visits to urgent care, treatment with pain medication, anti-inflammatories, steroids. MRI Referral to Neruologist Referral for hearing test (appointment is upcoming) Referral to ENT specialist (appointment is upcoming)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient presented to the Emergency Department several hours after receiving their first dose of Pfizer's COVID-19 vaccine. In the ED, the patient reported heart palpitations, "seeing spots", chest discomfort, itching on their chest, and HTN. On presentation, the patient was tachycardic (120bpm) and hypertensive (185/95). The patient's labs and tests were not concerning, and the physician stated the patient was well-appearing and in no acute distress. The patient was discharged with diagnoses of possible reaction Pfizer COVID vaccine, Possible anxiety response, and Hypertension. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was passenger in car with husband. It began forty min after I had shot and lasted about 4-5 min. It started with a little tingling on my upper lip. It then moved from there to some slight pressure in my nose and then moved from nose to throat that felt scratchy. It appeared to me to be an allergic reaction, rather mild. It did not trigger an asthmatic response and as it moved from one spot to the next, the symptom at the prior spot ended.  I have had no other issue since then.  Today, the day after the shot, my arm is a little sore if I lift it. I was a little tired last night but that is it. I contacted the pharmacy this morning after thinking about it through the night as I thought it was an event that should possibly be reported.  They asked that I fill this out which I am doing. Will it be OK for me to have the second vaccine? If so, I would most likely like to have it in a physicians office. Is it possible to get it to the allergist I once used? I would feel comfortable with him giving it to me. If I have to see him in advance, I will make an appointment. I would love to chat with someone on this. THANK YOU.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: High Blood Glucose numbers. I work with a diabetic counselor who says that I am not the only person experiencing this.  I am hoping my numbers return to normal soon!

SYMPTOM_TEXT: April 6th, 2021     Today at about 2:43pm, one of our technicians came to me and stated that a customer (employee too) had just got her second COVID-19 shot (Moderna), and she was at her car and not feeling well. The patient's co-worker had told us that her finger tips were numb and that she had a headache. The technician asked the customer to come back in, which she did and sat down in a chair immediately in front of me. I went directly to talk to her, as another technician was helping in the clinical services room, drawing up more shots.       I asked the patient how she was feeling, and what she was feeling.  She said she did not feel well, that her finger tips were numb, and she had this incredible pounding in the back of her head, and she ran her hand over the lower back part of her head and neck.  She looked down and I asked her again how she was doing, she said not well, that she was beginning to get light headed and was looking a little pale.  I called to the pharmacy team for help, to clear out the clinical services room and asked the technician to help me slowly walk her to the room.  As we got her in the room I asked her if she would be ok to lay down on the floor and put her feet up in a chair, briefly explaining that this would help with the dizziness and keep her safe should she faint, because she would already be on the floor. another technician popped in and asked her if she could get her a cold cloth for her forehead, Patient said yes and the technician did so. an employee was working at the computer and just quietly stayed working (for another store).  I moved around him and got the Blood Pressure Machine.  I asked the patient if it would be ok it I monitored her blood pressure, she said yes. Patient was always 100% coherent and helped move her arm for me. I asked the employee for a piece of paper to document the reading, but the technician ran and got me one.  Her first set of vitals were high.  I marked them down and the employee told me the time.  I just sat on my knees next to the patient for a while and tried to comfort her. I asked her a couple of times if she felt any change, and she said yes,     Shot given 2:40pm     2:45pm BP 149/99 Pulse 71   SX:  fingers numb, pounding in the back of her head  cool cloth placed on forehead  calmed area down & quietly talked to the patient to determine how she was doing  ************************************************  (Patient volunteered that she had just gotten tested for COVID-19 and that she tested negative.) I asked patient how she was feeling and she said that she was feeling a little worse.  She said she was starting to get the shakes.  I asked her if she had gotten anything to eat on her lunch and she said no. I asked her if she felt like it and if her BP was good, how would she like a sip of juice.      ********************************************     I asked the patient how she was feeling and she stated that her tight felt ever so slightly tight, but she said "I am asthmatic, and it did not feel any different than what she had experienced before.   I took her BP/P again...  2:55pm BP 157/105 Pulse 68  I looked at the employee and he looked at me, and I told the patient that I would be right back.  I quickly went and consulted with the technician and we decided that we should call 911 due to the increased in BP, pulse lower and the change in symptoms.  The technician called 611 and talked to an employee and I called 911 and explained what was going on and what our need was.  (The technician and I quickly discussed that neither of us felt that she was having an allergic reaction, just an adverse reaction, Epi was not called for. ) Employee stated that the clinic recommended we give her Benadryl.  I did a fast check w/ the technician, it was not on our standing order/ protocol. Antihistamines can exacerbate asthma.) Then I went back to the patient.  By the time I had gotten off the phone with 911, 2 more employees were in the room, and the patient was just getting off the phone with her father.  Once I got positioned in the room, one employee left,  I asked one employee sit down in a chair and the other employee was by the door leading to the pharmacy.  I told the patient that we had called for an ambulance.  I briefly explained due to her BP/P and her symptoms changing.  I asked her if she wanted another cool cloth and she said yes.  I asked an employee to get one for her from the sink in the pharmacy.  I was again kneeling at her side.  I saw her eyes well up with tears and a few tears were running down her face.  I asked another employee to get me a paper towel, which he did, and I handed it to the patient.  I tried to reassure her that things would be ok and this was just to ensure that she was safe.  She stated that she felt a little nauseated.  I then took her BP/P again.  3:05PM  BP 146/99 P 66 2 employees and I remained with the patient, all calm and I made sure she knew we were there for her.  I am not sure the time the EMTs arrived, but another employee let us know and we opened the door to let them in.  They asked the patient a lot of questions and I gave them my sheet of what I had recorded for her blood pressure and pulse (BP/P).  They asked the patient if they would help her into a sitting position, she said yes, but it was an awkward position, so I asked the patient if it would be ok if I helped support her back, she said yes, and I did just that.  I stayed with the patient until they got her situated on the gurney and I helped cover up her legs.  I went back to work when the EMT's wheeled the patient away.     The BP/P is the best of my recollection, as the EMT's took my sheet of paper.     At no time did the patient ever exhibit difficulty breathing, labored breathing or any change in her breathing.  She was calm and her chief complaint was the numbness in her fingers and the pounding headache at the back of her head.
PRIOR_VAX: Moderna given 3.9.21 Lot 014m20a given in L arm... she did NOT tell us until she reacted to the second shot!!!

On March 23rd, 2021 I received my first dose of Moderna. After 5 minutes of receiving the 1st dose of Moderna, I began to experience some tightness in my throat. My mouth and lips experienced a tingling sensation.  As  I walked around the store passing time, I began to feel dizzy. After 15 minutes the dizziness subsided and the tightness of my throat was manageable, so I left the store. However, it took another hour for the tingling sensation to dissipate. Later that night I felt better, other than a sore arm. 3 days later on March 26th, I began to experience a small pinpoint rash across my torso and upper thighs.  It became quite itchy. My face also became flush as if I was sunburned. At night I felt as if I had hives trying to pop out across the back of my head along the hairline. I took Benadryl for a few nights and Allegra during the day to manage the itchiness.  The rash has since calmed down, however, there is still a faint rash that has become rough to the touch, and heat still brings it out again.

I then asked her if she wanted me to proceed with her second injection. that day and she said yes, and added it's one of those things that  unfortunately happen. Some people have a reaction and I happen to be one of them:end quote. I gave her co-worker their injection first, then I gave her injection. About 5 mins in she started saying she was hot. I offered her some water and she said she was getting hot. About 10 mins in she started saying that she feels nauseous and hot still. We put a wet paper towel  on the back of her neck. By that Time I has  staff were up front assisting me with patient. That is when I asked someone to grab the Epinephrine injection for stand by and proceeded to call 911. I gave them all the information about the patient, but noticed that she was telling the ladies that her throat was tightening up and it was becoming hard to breathe. Her breathing was becoming deep and fast as I watched her from the phone. That is  when I told one of them to give her the injections, because the patient was becoming unresponsive to our questions except for nodding of the head when asked can we inject her with the pen. After the injection was given, EMT was right at the door and started to triage the patient.  I informed them that the patient had just received the epinephrine shot not even 5 mins before they walked through the door and she was given the wet paper towels to keep her cool because she was saying she was hot. After that  another  vehicle arrived and asked  if she wanted to go to the Hospital and she said yes. They got her on the gurney and I gave them the information about what happened before they arrived along with her Injection card.
CUR_ILL: illness for 3 days after 1st COVID-19 shot 3 weeks ago
PRIOR_VAX: illness for 3 days after first COVID-19, 03/16/2021, COVID 19, Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine

Written by Doctor: April 7, 2021 2:09 p.m. DOB 2/07/1995, male, received his second dose of Moderna Vaccine (Lot 019B21A) at 1:13 p.m.  He stood up and walked to the usher?s table to have his vaccine card completed.  Approximately one minute after receiving his vaccine, he had a syncopal episode falling directly backwards striking his head on the floor.  I, MD did not directly witness the fall, but everyone who witnessed the fall said that he fell completely unimpeded to the floor.  I was notified and immediately assisted the patient who was with his girlfriend.  Patient initially appeared ?out?, but almost immediately opened his eyes and asked what happened.  His skin was cool and clammy.  A pulse oximeter was placed on his finger registering 98% o2 and a pulse of 53.  I kept him lying on the floor until he was completely awake and aware of his surroundings.  At the time he said his neck was not sore, but his head was sore.  Approximately 2-3 minutes later, we were able to assist him in standing to immediately sit down in a wheelchair.  He was taken to the cot in the hallway just outside the Medical Observation where I was able to help him to stand and then lie down.  An icepack was provided to put on the back of his head, he was provided water, Gatorade, and two cookies.  Patient said that he hadn?t eaten all day and had been feeling slightly hungry prior to his vaccination.  I had patient move all extremities and asked his questions to verify that he was full awake and oriented to person, place, and time.  Patient girlfriend  stayed with patient while he ate his cookies.  I addressed my concerns about patient striking his head on the floor and the possibility of a closed head injury.  Girlfriend felt that patient was now completely back to his normal state of mind.  I had patient remain lying down for 20 minutes.  When I returned to check on him, he was sitting up and wanted to leave.  I told him that he needed to be able to walk up and down the hallway before I would feel comfortable letting him leave.  He stood up and walked halfway down the hallway before saying he was lightheaded.  I immediately went to him to lead him back to the cot, but he insisted that he needed to use the bathroom to urinate.  Both girlfriend and I stood in the doorway to assist patient if he needed, but he was able to finish urinating, then returned and sat in the wheelchair.  I spoke to both Doctors via a phone call and had spoken to someone earlier.  After letting them know that patient did not want an ambulance called, but I was going to strongly recommend he go to the nearest ER before returning home, I returned to the patient.  Vital signs at 1:53 were Pulse Ox of 98%, pulse 78, and blood pressure sitting of 140/75.  Again, I strongly recommended that girlfriend drive him to an ED for an evaluation and possible cat scan.  Patient also now had some paracervical neck pain which I also said should be evaluated.  Patient and girlfriend both insisted they didn?t want an ambulance called and girlfriend felt comfortable taking patient out of the clinic.  Patient said he was hungry, and they were going to get food first.  Girlfriend gave me her phone number (xxx)xxx-xxxx and I gave her my phone number (xxx-xxx-xxxx).  I told her I was going to call her every hour to check on patient and told her to call me at any time.  I recommended acetaminophen for the headache and other vaccine symptoms but no ibuprofen because of the possible head injury.  I recommended to immediately call an ambulance or go to an ED for nausea, worsening headache, confusion, or drowsiness.  Girlfriend is not to let patient sleep longer than 30 minutes at a time.  Patient was able to walk out of the clinic easily under his own power without any assistance.  He stated he was feeling much better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Same as the first shot, however, the adverse effects started shortly after the 2nd shot (within 2 hours after 2nd shot, vs 12 hours after the 1st shot). The symptoms are as follows: Severe headache, severe fatigue and muscle ache, shortness of breath and mild dizziness.  Muscle pain is more noticeable at joints (knees, shoulder cuffs, ankles).  I probably couldn't walk more than 2 blocks before having to sit down and catch my breath. I probably can't stand for more than 5 minutes,  and most definitely not in a shape to be able to work (office /engineering). It is hard to pin point, but I would probably say my mind is foggy and not as sharp. However I can quantify this.  The above symptoms lasted 5 days after the first shot, however,  it took up to 14 days before I recovered from general fatigue.   As for second dose, I am filling this form 5 hours post injection.  Considering the severity and early onset of symptoms (compared to 1st dose) I can predict uneasy days to follow.  Note, I am 178cm, and 76Kgs and do not have health issues. My pain tolerance is much higher than an average person.
HISTORY: Depression since 19 years of age. Under complete control. Does not interfere with daily activities.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my first Moderna shot on March 24th. Just had a sore arm the next day.   April 2nd: Around 1pm at work I was starting to feel a headache coming on. By about 2-3pm it was worse and felt tired/drowsy. I ate supper then went to take a nap at 7:30pm. I woke up at about 10:30pm, checked the time and just felt out of it so I went right back to sleep.  April 3rd: I slept until my dog woke me at about 5:50am and felt pretty good, still minor headache and some chills. During the night I did feel some soreness in my arm that got the covid shot. After I showered I checked my arm and it was swelled up with a rash like redness maybe an inch in diameter. I was fine for most of the day enjoying the nice weather outside. Then about 6pm I started to feel the headache again and some chills. Went to bed at about 10:30pm, headache was bad, had the chills, started coughing some, and just didn?t feel normal, took some Tylenol to help through the night.  April 4th: Slept through the night fine, woke up with a mild headache and a sore throat. Had some dry coughs occasionally throughout the day, but was fine most of the day.  I did check my temperature throughout these past few days and all check were normal.  April 5th: Almost back to normal, still have a sore throat and cough. My arm rash near the shot area has gone away, just a little swollen.  April 6th: Back to normal health.

About a week (6 days) after I had my first Moderna shot, Inflammation of the hands and fingers started in the forms or red/skin color welts like Hives. Excessive burning and itching sensations, difficult even to wash or rub hands together, scratching was increasing the pain and was resulting in swelling of fingers. Fingertips had pain gotten super sensitive with inflammation.  Couldn't even form my fist because of swelling and pain. Had a lot of discomfort and difficulty sleeping so took a Tylenol PM one night to reduce the inflammation and to aid the sleep. Only took it once as not much of a fan of medicines. I also soaked my hands in water with baking soda which provided some comfort and reduced the pain and inflammation, applied some coconut oil to soothe the inflammation.  As I thought it was happening because of hives and/or excessive heat increase in the body, I changed my diets, started with foods and ingredients that cools down the body which felt like working and the swelling, pain, burning/itching sensations were slowly pacifying in 3-4 days. I also got acupuncture treatment after 5 days which has helped a lot now. Now after a week and all that I did, I don't feel the pain and burning sensations anymore, no swelling and the skin is getting clear, red spots/welts are disappearing and I am able to sleep better.
OTHER_MEDS: No medications, just some regular herbal remedies and dietary supplements and spices for example, Ginger, Turmeric, Terminalia Arjuna, Cumin, Ghee, Coriander, etc.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the vaccine around 10:00 AM. Her husband was vaccinated immediately after her. We explained to the husband that they needed to wait around about 15 minutes to make sure they did not have any issues with the vaccine. She asked where the bathroom was while he was being vaccinated. When he was done with his vaccine, I was helping another patient register for his covid vaccine. The husband came running to the counter and stated his wife had called and said she woke up on the bathroom floor. So I immediately came and told RPH on duty and called 911.  Then went and checked on the patient and asked what happened and I told her I called EMS and they were going to come check on her to make sure she was okay. I then went and told the store manager what had occurred.  EMS came and checked on her and took her vitals and asked if she needed to be transported to the hospital at which time she declined and said she was okay. We told her that if she felt bad later to call 911, or call her doctor. The husband then took her home.

Frankly, I regret getting the vaccine, wish i had not.   I had covid last March, it was no big deal beyond what a flu would have done...with some shortness of breath on and off for a few months. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On 4/8/21 Physician was administering Covid-19 vaccines at our clinic in the lawn and garden center.  She had a patient who was there to receive her first dose of the vaccine.  After the vaccine was administered, she was okay and went to sit in the waiting area.  Shortly later she came back up to the pharmacist table and reported feeling dizzy, lightheaded and nauseous.  Physician then told the patient to sit right by her so she could keep a better eye on her.  The patient said she was okay and then suddenly she passed out.  Physician was able to catch her as she was falling out of the chair and was able to lay her down on the floor.  She may have bumped her head slightly on the ground during this process.  Physician then reports that the patient's breathing sounded labored, and the patient was not conscious.  At that point Emergency department was called.  Physician removed the patients mask and was preparing to administer an EpiPen due to the labored breathing but then the patient regained consciousness.  The Emergency operator advised her to keep the patient on the ground until EMS arrived on scene.  Patient was conscious and okay on the ground.  EMS then came and took care of the patient.  It was deemed that the patient gets lightheaded when she gets bloodwork done usually and believes this may have been an anxiety event. She did not want to go to the hospital.  She felt a bit dizzy once she was sitting back upright and EMS approved the patient drinking some water.  This seemed to help, and the patients color came back.  The patient sat with Physician for a while and then felt back to normal and left on her own accord.

C) Over the following 2 days, symptoms continued to worsen: swelling of lymph nodes on both sides of the neck, under left and right arm (right more painful than left) and lymph nodes near pubic area - right side. Excruciating pain in all muscles of the body, particularly neck, head, right side of the torso and right arm. This affected my ability to breathe (shallow breath, unable to take a deep breath). Symptoms started to disappear after 4 days. It took a total of 10 days to recover full mobility of my right arm. Traces of the rash are still visible 5 months after injection.

No adverse reaction, this was a medication error because it was administered too early. It is difficult to determine the cause of that error because it occurred more than 1 year ago. However, the subsequent doses could have been prevented by more education of resources. In summary a repeated dose (3rd dose) on 4/30/20 should not have been administered until 9/3/20 and was counted as invalid according to system due to not being 6 months from previous dose. Patient then came in for Hepatitis A on 4/7/21. This was administered (4th dose) due to previous doses being invalid and system forecaster recommending administration to complete series.  It was found that that our EMR care gaps section did not recommend administration on 4/7/21. ACIP recommendations state the following: "If the first and second doses of hepatitis A vaccine were administered less than 6 months apart, the second dose is invalid and should be repeated 6 months after the invalid second dose (7). However, if this repeat dose (the third dose) is administered anytime 6 months or more after the first dose, the series can be considered complete." In addition to needing to know extra resources, system forecaster should only be cautiously utilized unless it is updated to include ACIP recommendations. If it was, we could have prevented a 4th dose for that patient.

If that had no effect, I would've been non-functional.    I didn't report it at the time.  When I saw my internist for a yearly exam, I told her and did a follow-up in an email.  I wanted her to understand it how incapacitated I was.  I have a profound hearing loss (hence, the cochlear implant).  I have no doubt this was due to ototoxicity of the vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is an 18 year old female with no PMHx that presented with lightheadedness and three subsequent episodes of syncope approximately 3-10 minutes post-vaccination. Patient was found to have an abrasion to the outer corner of her right eyebrow following an unwitnessed. It was unknown if patient was seated or standing at the time. The nurse first on scene states the patient lost consciousness briefly again and experienced approximately 10 seconds of upper extremity muscle contractions (described as convulsions). Patient experienced a loss of bladder control upon loss of consciousness. Patient was lowered to the ground to be in a supine position by healthcare staff. At this time, patient was alert and oriented without agitation or confusion. Patient denies memory of the event. She states she had prior episodes of fainting after blood draw.   Patient has no allergies to medication or food. No past surgical history. No prior hospitalizations. Denies personal and family history seizure disorders, cardiac disturbances, and hypoglycemic or hyperglycemic events.   Patient was hooked up to cardiac monitor and found to be in normal sinus rhythm with a heart rate of 64bpm.  Vitals Orthostatic BP measurements Lying supine - 110/72 Seated - 124/76 Standing - 128/72  HR: 64 bpm RR: 16 breaths/min without distress SO2: 99%  On examination, patient was A&Ox3 without lethargy, agitation, or confusion. Patient has an abrasion to the superior aspect of the right orbit (outer eyebrow) without laceration or bleeding.  Patient was diaphoretic and pale following event. Normal cardiac rate and rhythm. Radial pulses intact, strong and equal bilaterally. No obvious nystagmus. Upon standing, patient steady on her feet without abnormal gait.

She was discharged to go home.  On 4/8/2021 her temp was 104.  She had brain fog.  She went back to same ER.  They did the same test. She never had any type of symptom normal to having pneumonia.  She was put on antibiotics and something for nausea.  Her fever and headache finally broke after about 5 days.  She had no strength and was basically laid up sick for almost a month.  She feels like she had a bad reaction to the covid vax since she had a viral lung infection with typical pneumonia symptoms.

I sat my phone down on my lap and was just looking about. I began at that point (2 1/2-3 mins mark) seeing the tile floor morph; the blue tiles and the green tiles kept merging together and forming one color. Then my heart raced, immediately and I started having hot flashes that shot out my ears. My heart raced even more and at that point I had realized something wasn?t right. A National Guards member came up to me and had asked if I were okay, I explained I was not and something was not right. They took me to a medical area and made me take deep breaths, and made me drink some water. My BP was high, and my Pulse Ox had dropped slightly, and then went straight back to normal once they had asked me to stick my head between my knees and keep breathing deeply. Also, both of my ears had turned deep red/purple and they were VERY warm to the touch. They felt as if heat were tunneling out of them. The only way I can explain truly how I felt, and I have NEVER done it fully, I felt as if I was fainting. Out of nowhere I felt as if I was going to pass out ? but it didn?t happen. The entire ?spell? lasted about 20 mins? I was monitored for an additional 40 minutes and was allowed to leave.
LAB_DATA: Just the medical help to drink water and wait an additional 40 minutes before leaving.

The patient came in for J&J vaccine. He said he had no history of severe allergic reaction to anything, including meds, food, vaccines or any injections.  He said that he did not receive any other vaccine in the past 14 days. According to the patient, he did not have test positive for Covid or was in contact with anyone with Covid for the past 2 weeks. He appeared perfectly fine prior to receiving the vaccine. Once the vaccine was given, within about 5 seconds, he said that he was seeing spots, he closed his eyes and made sounds that were similar to snoring. His neck was completely down on his right side and he almost fell off his chair. I held him so he would not fall off the chair and called for help.  A few of the co-workers came to hold him. He was non responsive and my co-workers helped to put his legs on the chair. At point, I gave him an epipen. Once the epipen was given, he opened his eyes in about few seconds and became responsive. The nurses came and took over at this point.  I stayed with him and the nurses for a few minutes. The patient was fully responsive and talking by the time I left the nurses and the patient. 911 was activated after the first epipen was given.  The patient was then evaluated by EMS and the onsite nurses. The patient was AOx4 with stable vital signs.  The patient had orthostatic vital signs taken and were within normal limits.  The patient demonstrated that he was able to ambulate with no assistance.  The patient signed a refusal for transport to the hospital and was driven home by a colleague.  The patient remains in care of that colleague for monitoring.  The patient was instructed that if he were to begin feeling the previous symptoms that he is to activate 911 and be seen in a hospital.  Patient understood the instructions and went back to his residence.

Client received the COVID vaccine (Janssen, Lot# 1808980) at 11:30. EMT observed the client sitting with her head in her hands and alerted RN, then all responded at 1140. The client complained of shortness of breath and dizziness. Upon assessment, the client was pale, diaphoretic, and clammy, and her skin was cool and dry. The client stated that she is anxious about needles and vaccinations, and that her mask was making her feel "claustrophobic." The client was encouraged to practice deep breathing and her vital signs were obtained: blood pressure of 96/76, respiratory rate of 12. The client stated that she did eat breakfast that morning at 0930 and was offered some water to drink. . Per the client, she has a medical history of hypothyroidism and the only medication she takes is levothyroxine. The client also stated that she tends to have lower blood pressure and "110/60 is normal" for her. The client was alert and oriented. At 1145, the repeat vital blood pressure for the client was 97/63. She stated at this time that she felt like she was going to pass out, and was transferred to the reclining chair. At 1150, the repeat vital signs were as follows: blood pressure of 118/80, heart rate of 78, respiratory rate of 16, and pulse O2 reading of 95%. At 1155, repeat vital signs were as follows: blood pressure of 112/74, heart rate of 78, respiratory rate of 14, pulse oximeter reading of 96%. At this time, the client's color returned to normal and they were no longer clammy. At 1207, the client's blood pressure was 110/72, their heart rate was 73, their respiratory rate was 8, and their pulse oximeter reading was 97%. The client stated they "feel great" and left the facility at 1210, ambulating with a steady gait to their car, where they were driven home by an acquaintance.

pt presented to clinic for 2nd moderna covid vaccine today and informed the covid  nurse about the complication from the 1st covid moderna vaccine given by another  nurse volunteer on 3/11/2021.  I was informed about this complication and spoke  to pt about history and symptoms.  pt stated that she had soreness for 2 days after the first injection but then  became more concerned when the pain lasts or more than 1 week and it's too  painful to perform ROM.  saw her PCP and there's concern that the deltoid  injection was given too high on ther deltoid region and thought it may have hit  the nerve and/or tenden sheath.  pt was eventually referred to allergist and  orthopedics. Given oral prednisone with no significnat relief.  Allergist didn't  think it's an allergy from the moderna vaccine.  pt was evlauated by ortho and  had an in-office ultrasound with unremarkable finding so she's referred to an  outside ultrasound study to be read by a radiologist.  pt has been icing the area, no warm compression.  being told to perforom ROM  exercise at home by ortho.  Thought of providing intraarticualr steroid injection  but ortho would like to wait until after pt obtain the 2nd covid vaccine.  Pt  stated that her pain is not as acute as it's initially presented.  pt's PCP has  mentioned about filing a VAER report but isn't sure if such report is done.  Plan:  discussed with pt that there's a possible IM technique issue by the nurse  volunteer giving the vacicne and plan to discuss further with the nurse when  she's in office next time (tomorrow?).  Also discuss with pt about possible COVID  vaccine complication, will have the contractor RN to file a VAER report just in  case PCP did not file one.  Pt cannot take NSAID due to kidney isssue. Encourage  heat compression and may alternate with cold compression.  Continue ROM exercise  including walking on the walll with fingers from anterior and lateral approach.  Encourage pt to continue following up with ortho and let us know in 1-2 weeks  whether pt is feeling better or worse.  pt verbalized understanding to plan.

I experienced this rather immediate unexpected gradually increasing dizziness with impaired balance while walking at accustomed pace over approximately 12-15 minute time period.  I was compelled to leave the track and lay down on an exercise mat where fortunately my wife came by t Within half hour of this attack i coiuld not stand and walk independently without support. My first time to a hospital ER  in my 78 years of life. Recommended for observation and additional tests I stay overnight in observation unit. Diagnosis appeared to be perplexing for physicians.  My wife  came by to assist me in standing , walking to the car and driving me to nearby ER. What happened to me was a frightening, anxiety-producing and dangerous situation. I could have easily fallen with substantial head or other bodily injury. Being in excellent health and with nothing else unusual having occurred recently to affect my general health (no changes, no illnesses), I cannot help conclude this episode was a serious adverse reaction to my 2nd Moderna vaccination.  I now consider what happened on 3/28/21 a "Vestibular Attack". I think possibly my body for some reason related to the vaccine might have been attacking itself, if that makes sense to scientists.  I hope this doesn't happen to others. I am not anti-vaccination. But individuals should be warned about this possible dangerous reaction or adverse side effect, which in my case did not occur immediately after the 2nd Moderna dose. I've complained to the hospital that possibility of severe dizziness with extreme loss of balance being related to recent Moderna 2nd vaccination was NOT discussed or commented.
LAB_DATA: Heart functioning, Brain MRI(to rule out strokes) and Blood tests all essentially negative. Dehydration suspected but no urinalysis to confirm. I think this minor. TIA's not seen in MRI but conjectured as possible. No evidence of stroke.   Orthostatic-hypotension?  Much more than that.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: First injection's adverts effects, Temp VAERS E-report number  339683.  **REACTIONS TO 2ND VACCINE:  (I opted to stay for observation for an hour, in case an EpiPen was needed. I have no prior history of anaphylaxis. I hadn't heard from moderna or CDC prior to 2nd shot, so felt it was best to err on the side of caution)  *oral numbness beginning 5 minutes after shot  *full oral numbness, and back of throat numbness, by 10min. Full numbness like with novocain injections.  *felt suddenly faint at about 10 minutes post vaccine, subsided at about 30 minutes post vaccine.  *lips tingling by 8 minutes post vaccine.  *lips numb by 10 minutes.  *facial tingling (cheeks and nose) about 15 minutes.  *numb cheeks and nose by about 20 minutes post vaccine.   *facial numbness lasted about 18 hours, oral numbness lasted almost 36 hours. Similar to the first shot but more intense and came on faster.   *arm soreness and injection site redness has not subsided 4 days out. Starting day 3 in the evening, the redness is spreading and feels like deep bruising. This seems to be in line with delayed cutaneous hypersensitivity, in my non-professional opinion. Day 4 it has spread further. Pictures are attached, if they help for documentation reasons.   *most other side effects experienced are well documented to be expected: these side effects were more intense than shot #1- nausea, diarrhea, fever (100.2), chills, aches, fatigue, headache, arm pain and redness, etc. I do feel that my immune system response going wonky has triggered a vaginal yeast infection post vaccine (only ever experienced this 2 other times in my life, also when my immune system took a hit).
HISTORY: Fibromyalgia diagnosed, unknown immune issues undiagnosed, asthma diagnosed, hereditary blood disorder undiagnosed but mother is diagnosed.
PRIOR_VAX: The 1st moderna shot, Temp VAERS E-report number  339683

They gave me a shot of Benadryl and I started to feel better after about 15 minutes. They said I should go to hospital. By the time I got to hospital I was feeling bad again. Patient received Janssen lot#1805020 with expiration of 05/25/2021 at 1420 sitting in upright chair. Vaccinator was notified that he has a history of vasovagal response with needles. This response presents itself as sweating (and possible fainting) and is alleviated by lying down. Client mentioned that previous nurse advised him to smell an alcohol pad to distract and prevent a vasovagal response, as this had worked previously on a glucose check. No medications were disclosed or history of anaphylaxis reported. With this background information, RN offered to have vaccine administered in reclined position, however client refused. RN conferred with co-lead about administration recommendations. Vaccinator then checked in with patient at 1423 to see if patient was okay and patient did not answer the question. RN then felt the client's hand and noticed hand was clammy. At 1425 the reclining chair was brought to the station and patient was transferred into chair, appearing diaphoretic. RN palpated pulse and noted patient was not tachycardia, but RN did note tachypnea and uneasiness. RN then provided distraction and promoted relaxation. Then at 1426 patient reported feeling okay and RN noted patient no longer felt clammy. At 1440 patient was asked if he would prefer if EMS should be called, patient declined and stated that he was able to drive home. Then at 1447 patient left the site appearing well, alert and oriented x3 leaving by self in private car.

Thrombocytopenia; several 5 mm purpuric blisters inside his mouth and on the inside upper lip, as well as small purpura at the site of an adhesive bandage on his left upper arm; petechiae on his bilateral lower extremities; bleeding oral blisters; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of thrombocytopenia in a 63-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. Acute Immune Thrombocytopenia following administration of Shingrix recombinant zoster vaccine.;  :  .DOI: 10.1002/ajh.26143)   The patient's past medical history included open angle glaucoma and hypercholesterolemia. Concurrent medical conditions included basal cell carcinoma.   On 1st September 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 15th September 2020, 14 days after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced thrombocytopenia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), purpura (serious criteria hospitalization) and petechia (serious criteria hospitalization). In September 2020, the patient experienced blood blister (serious criteria hospitalization). The patient was treated with dexamethasone and immunoglobulins nos (Ivig). On 4th December 2020, the outcome of the thrombocytopenia was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the blood blister, purpura and petechia were recovered/resolved.   The reporter considered the thrombocytopenia, blood blister, purpura and petechia to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of acute immune thrombocytopenia in a 63-years old male patient, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis. The patient had a history of basal cell carcinomas of multiple skin sites, open-angle glaucoma, and hypercholesterolemia. No information on patient's medical history, family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On 1st September 2020, the patient received initial recombinant zoster (Shingrix) Vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided but it could be 62 years or 63 years. On 15th September 2020, about 2 weeks after the vaccination, the patient presented to primary care physician with observation of bleeding oral blisters. The patient did not report any other abnormal bleeding or bruising, or associated fevers, chills, anorexia or weight loss. Physical exam revealed several 5 mm purpuric blisters inside his mouth and on the inside upper lip, as well as small purpura at the site of an adhesive bandage on his left upper arm, and petechiae on his bilateral lower extremities. A complete blood count (CBC) revealed a platelet count of 1000/uL. White blood cell count and hemoglobin were within normal limits. The patient was admitted to the general medicine service at which point Hematology was consulted. Review of the peripheral blood smear showed severe thrombocytopenia with rare large and giant platelets. Erythrocyte morphology was normal and there were no schistocytes or evidence of dysplasia. Isolated severe thrombocytopenia with giant platelets on the peripheral blood smear was thought to be consistent with ITP and Hematology recommended starting dexamethasone 40 mg daily with a plan to complete 4 days. The patient received 5 days of dexamethasone 40 mg daily between 15th September 20202 and 19th September 2020, and an extra dose was administered due to an order duplication. During this time his platelet count remained in the 0-1000/uL range. Given the lack of improvement in his platelet count and concern for risk of bleeding, he received IVIG 1 g/kg (total dose 75 g) on 21st September 2020. On 22nd September 2020 his platelet count had increased to 25000/uL, and he was discharged home on 23rd September 2020 with a platelet count of 30000/uL. On follow-up 29th September 2020 platelets had increased to 5900/uL and subsequently normalized at 268000/uL on 4th December 2020. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization. The author's commented, "While ITP following zoster vaccine has not been previously described, the temporal relation between administration of the shingles vaccine with development of ITP about 2 weeks later does suggest causality, particularly without other obvious triggers. Thrombocytopenia has been described following infection with varicella zoster in children both during acute infection and as a post-infectious sequelae occurring days to weeks after symptom resolution. The mechanism is thought to be development of IgG and IgM directed against platelet surface glycoproteins which occurs in the setting of viremia. Shingrix recombinant zoster vaccine does not contain live virus but rather contains zoster glycoprotein E combined with adjuvant ASO1B to promote sustained immune response. It stands to reason that this vaccine would induce a similar immune response as is seen in varicella zoster infection and may therefore induce IgG and IgM directed against platelet surface glycoproteins resulting in acute ITP. The patient in this case achieved a complete remission of his acute ITP following treatment with dexamethasone and IVIG."

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Metabolic acidosis; Weakness; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of metabolic acidosis in a adult patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The subject's past medical history included allogenic stem cell transplantation.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On an unknown date, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced metabolic acidosis (serious criteria hospitalization) and weakness (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the metabolic acidosis and weakness were unknown.   The reporter considered the metabolic acidosis and weakness to be possibly related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Metabolic acidosis; Weakness, in a patient of unspecified age and gender, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis.  The patient was a part of a single-center prospective observational cohort study that was conducted between December of 2018 and June of 2020 to evaluate the safety and reactogenicity of recombinant zoster vaccine (RZV) in adult allogeneic hematopoietic cell transplantation (HCT) recipients, including any effects on graft-versus-host disease (GVHD) occurrence or exacerbation given the presence of an adjuvant. The patient was more than or equal to 18-year-old at the time of allogenic HCT. The patient was between 9 to 24 months from time to transplant and was deemed appropriate for RZV by treating clinician. The patient did not have disease relapse prior to administration of the first dose of RZV vaccination (V1). No information on patient medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received 1 intramuscular dose (0.5 mL) of Shingrix (administration site unspecified, batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported. [In this study, Cohort A consisted of patients who received V1 at 9 to 12 months after transplant in accordance with a hospital vaccination guidelines. Cohort B consisted of patients who received V1 at 12 to 24 months after transplant as part of a "catch-up" vaccination effort. RZV was given alongside other vaccines in the vaccine schedule. Patients were followed until June of 2020 and for more than or equal to 30 days after final vaccination. The primary end points were safety and reactogenicity in the total vaccinated cohort (TVC), which included all participants who received more than or equal to 1 vaccine dose. The secondary end points included incidence and severity of GVHD in the TVC compared with historical controls and the incidence rates of HZ in the TVC and modified TVC (mTVC), which included only patients who received both doses of the vaccine. Adult Post Hematopoietic Cell Transplant Vaccine Guidelines included: 9 months vaccine as DTaP, HiB, IPV, Prevnar, Shingrix; 12 months vaccine as DTaP, HiB, IPV, Prevnar, Menactra, Twinrix, Shingrix; 14 months vaccines as Hep B, Menactra; 18 months vaccines as DTaP, HiB, IPV, Prevnar, Twinrix and 24 months vaccines as MMR, Pneumovax]. On an unknown date, 3 days after vaccination (V1), the patient was hospitalized for metabolic acidosis and weakness. [In this study, HZ cases were defined as (1) a new rash that was characteristic (unilateral, dermatomal, painful, vesicular) and that was documented as HZ by a treating clinician or (2) an atypical rash or suspected disseminated VZV infection that was confirmed by VZV culture, direct fluorescent antibody detection, polymerase chain reaction, or immunohistochemical staining on tissue specimen. Patients who had HZ within 30 days of vaccine 2 (V2) were excluded from the mTVC analysis. A sensitivity analysis was performed looking at follow-up only in individuals who discontinued antiviral prophylaxis. During the study period, there were 5 deaths; they were secondary to disease relapse and infection and were not considered related to vaccination]. The case was considered as serious due to hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. Outcome of the event was not reported. The events were considered as possibly related to vaccination. The authors commented "Two doses of RZV demonstrated safety and tolerability in allogeneic HCT without increased rates of chronic GVHD (cGVHD), relapse, or death, as well as overall low rates of breakthrough. Vaccines were co-administered with RZV in the majority of participants which may have led to a higher incidence of solicited AEs than if RZV was administered alone. Although there have been concerns related to potential immune-mediated disorders (pIMDs) with the use of the RZV novel adjuvant AS01B system, there was no increased incidence or severity of cGVHD observed in the subgroup that was vaccinated between 9 and 12 months compared with historical controls in the peri-vaccination 9 to 15-month period. This finding is in keeping with renal transplant recipients who did not experience higher rates of solid organ rejection21 and healthy adults who did not have increased pIMDs after RZV. Patients on immunosuppression during vaccination had a higher incidence rate ratios (IRR) of cGVHD in the peri-vaccination period compared with those not on immunosuppression; however, they also likely represent a cohort with a higher baseline risk for alloreactivity.". The authors concluded "In summary, among recipients of allogeneic HCT, RZV was safe, tolerable, and did not increase rates of GVHD. There were few breakthrough cases of HZ in this cohort; however, future RCTs are needed to determine vaccine efficacy.". This article is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction. This is 1 of the 6 valid cases reported in this literature article; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021GSK065760:Same reporter US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021GSK065761:Same reporter US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021GSK065762:Same reporter
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Allogenic stem cell transplantation

severe hypertension; Thrombotic Microangiopathy; hemolytic anemia; thrombocytopenia; hematuria; proteinuria; leukocytosis; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of thrombotic microangiopathy in a 5-month-old female patient who received Flu unspecified (Influenza vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Hib UNK (Hib vaccine) (batch number UNK, expiry date unknown) for prophylaxis and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE (PREVENAR) (batch number UNK, expiry date unknown) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included spinal muscular atrophy (treated with Onasemnogene abeparvovec) and pneumonia. Concomitant products included prednisolone.   On an unknown date, the patient received Influenza vaccine, Hib vaccine and PREVENAR. On an unknown date, 1 day after receiving Influenza vaccine and Hib vaccine, the patient experienced thrombotic microangiopathy (serious criteria GSK medically significant), hemolytic anemia (serious criteria GSK medically significant), thrombocytopenia (serious criteria GSK medically significant), hematuria, proteinuria, leukocytosis and hypertension. The patient was treated with operations and procedures (Plasmapheresis (Nos)), red blood cells (Red Blood Cell), platelets, human blood (Platelet Transfusion), glucocorticoids nos (Glucocorticoids), diuretics nos (Diuretic) and antihypertensives nos (Antihypertensives). On an unknown date, the outcome of the thrombotic microangiopathy, hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, hematuria, proteinuria and leukocytosis were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the hypertension was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the thrombotic microangiopathy, hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, hematuria, proteinuria, leukocytosis and hypertension to be related to Influenza vaccine and Hib vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Thrombotic Microangiopathy (TMA), in a 5-month-old female patient, who was vaccinated with Unspecified Influenza vaccine; Unspecified Hemophilus influenza B (Hib) vaccine (manufacturer unknown for both) for prophylaxis.  The patient had Spinal Muscular Atrophy. The patient received prednisolone 1 day prior to and for a minimum of 30 days following treatment with 1.1X10E14 vg/kg of onasemnogene abeparvovec. The patient was treated with onasemnogene abeparvovec while hospitalized and undergoing treatment for aspiration pneumonia. Second event of pneumonia 3 d after dosing. The patient had another episode of pneumonia 3 days after onasemnogene infusion. Four days before dosing, the patient sputum culture grew Proteus and Acinetobacter species (Aspiration pneumonia 4 d before dosing; (Acinetobacter baumannii and Pasteurella). The patient weight at onasemnogene abeparvovec dosing was 6.5 kg. The patient did not have Nusinersen (most recent dose). The source of report was registry of patients with spinal muscular atrophy receiving disease-modifying therapies. No information on patient family history concomitant medication was reported.   On an unknown date, 6 days after receiving onasemnogene abeparvovec, the patient received Unspecified Influenza vaccine; Unspecified Hemophilus influenza B (Hib) vaccine. The patient also received Prevenar vaccine (administration site unspecified, dose number unknown; batch number not provided for all).  The age at vaccination was not provided but it could be between 4 months or 5 months at the time of vaccination.  On an unspecified date, seven days after onasemnogene infusion, 1 day after vaccination, the patient developed TMA with hemolytic anemia, hematuria, proteinuria, leukocytosis, thrombocytopenia, and severe hypertension. Renal ultrasound scan indicated diffuse increase in cortical echogenicity bilaterally. Laboratory evidence of TMA (baseline and following onasemnogene abeparvovec): Haemoglobin: Baseline: 10.3 g/dL, Nadir: 7 g/dL (day 7); platelet: Baseline: 503 k/mcL, Nadir: 17 k/mcL; Creatining: Baseline: 0.1 mg/dL, Peak: 0.7 mg/dL; Lactate dehydrogenase (LDH): Peak: 4208 U/L. Urinalysis showed Protein and blood. Prothrombin time (PT), Partial thromboplastin time (PTT) and International normalized ratio (INR) were normal. Acute complement pathway investigations (classic/alternative) at presentation of TMA: Complement (C3): 1.1 g/L (ref 0.9-1.8) ; Complement (C4): 0.07 (ref 0.15-0.57) ; Bb fragment concentration: 3.8 mg/L (ref less than 2.2); Soluble C5b-9: 0.9 mg/L (ref less than 0.3); CH50: 160 U eq/mL (ref more than70); FH autoantibody less than 50 AU (ref less than 200 AU); Factor B: 32.3 mg/dL (ref 22-50); Factor H: 369 mg/L (ref 180-420); Factor I: 34 mg/L (ref 16-40). Investigations concerning potential predisposition factors (hereditary or acquired): Functional complement assay with low C4, and normal C3, CFH, I, neg anti-complement factor H autoantibody (CFHAb), CH50, high C3b-9 (SMAC), a disintegrin and metalloproteinase with thrombospondin motifs 13 (ADAMTS13) normal. No genetic testing completed. Stool and urine cultures negative. The features of TMA resolved within 2 weeks following plasmapheresis, except hypertension, which continued to persist 1 year later. Functional TMA panel indicated evidence of complement pathway activation with no autoantibodies or abnormal complement components. Genetic evaluation was not performed.  Treatment included packed red blood cell (PRBC) and platelet transfusions, glucocorticoids, plasmapheresis, diuretic for fluid overload, antihypertensives.  Outcome from the time of diagnosis: Recovered (2 week) with persistent hypertension.  The authors commented "We have reported 3 children with SMA who developed TMA following onasemnogene abeparvovec therapy. These cases share several similarities. TMA developed approximately 1 week following onasemnogene abeparvovec infusion, 2 of the 3 children suffered from vomiting, 2 of the 3 had previous exposure to nusinersen, and 2 had infections with encapsulated organisms. Patient 1 had an infection preceding TMA with a new infection shortly after infusion. Drug-induced TMA is theorized to result from immune-mediated reactions or a dose-/duration-dependent direct toxic effect. Differentiating criteria include early temporal association with drug administration in the former as opposed to a delayed onset from a cumulative exposure in the latter. Our 3 patients developed TMA approximately 1 week after administration, suggesting an immune-mediated etiology. Other causes and presentations of TMA include hemolytic uremic syndrome resulting from shiga toxin-positive E coli; thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura resulting from a reduction of ADAMTS13, the protease that cleaves von Willebrand factor (vWF); hereditary deficiencies in regulation of coagulation or alternative complement pathways; and a wide variety of infectious pathogens, including encapsulated organisms. In addition to exposure to onasemnogene abeparvovec, each of the 3 patients had contributory factors that could be putatively associated with TMA. Potential triggering factors include concurrent infection with encapsulated bacteria and recent vaccine exposure. It is unknown what additional risks to onasemnogene abeparvovec, if any, previous exposure to nusinersen confers. If thrombocytopenia is present and there is a clinical suspicion of TMA, further evaluation including hemoglobin hemoglobin and testing for hemolysis and renal dysfunction (including urinalysis) also should be obtained. Early recognition of TMA is imperative, as TMA may require therapeutic intervention such as plasmapheresis, dialysis, or pharmacotherapy, to lessen associated morbidity and mortality".
