SYMPTOM_TEXT: large left horseshoe tear on the retina in the left/tear on the right retina/small tear right eye; detached retina on the left; vision loss/can't see at all/thought he was going blind; streaks of lightening; section of vision lost in the left eye; Posterior Vitreous Detachment; floaters; sick; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient wife). A 60-years-old male patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 MRNA VACCINE, Solution for injection) dose 1 via an unspecified route of administration on 06Jan2021 (Lot Number: EJ1685, expiry date not reported) as single dose; and dose 2 via an unspecified route of administration on 29Jan2021 (lot Number: EL8982, expiry date not reported) as single dose; for covid-19 immunization. Medical history included eye surgery (he already had surgery once) from an unknown date and unknown if ongoing. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. Patient received first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on 06Jan2021 then on 29Jan2021 the 2nd dose. He experienced side effects: floaters on 06Jan2021, and streaks of lightening then vision loss on 15Mar2021. There was a large left horseshoe tear on the retina in the left and a detached retina on the left and a tear on the right retina on 19Mar2021. He already had surgery once. He will have 2nd surgery on the other eye. Reporter reported a follow up.  He can't see at all. He was recovering and has to lay on face for 2 weeks. Reporter stated she read about retina problems related to the virus but not to the vaccine, could not find information. Patient was a retail pharmacist. He deals with customers and several customers stated they had vision problems with the vaccine: double vision, loss of sight. "There was a problem out there, but maybe they were not reporting it took reporter 2 hours to report so they may not have the time to sit there to report". Reporter knew they can't prove it was the vaccine that caused it. Reporter don't believe in coincidences. It seemed quite obvious to them it's related to the vaccine. Reporter appreciated all the help and stated they didn't have all the answers.  Reporter sure it was the vaccine because it was within hours after the first vaccine, but since there was no information regarding the sight problems related to the vaccine patient didn't think about it. Then the floaters got worse and started to block his vision, after the 2nd vaccine it was dramatically; within hours it was worse. He's never been sick in 36 years (2021). Patient hoped no one else has to deal with what he has to deal with. Patient also reported that on 10Feb2021, patient had section of vision lost in the left eye. It was then reported that patient was well versed in the virus and the vaccine. He was unable to speak on the phone at this time as he was recovering from surgery. Patient received the first dose of the Pfizer COVID 19 vaccine on 6Jan2021 and right away began seeing hundreds of floaters. He didn't correlate it to the vaccine but it didn't go away. Then he received the second dose of the vaccine on 29Jan2021 and within hours he thought he was going blind. He went to an optometrist 01Feb2021 who sloughed off the idea of it being related to the vaccine and diagnosed him with Posterior Vitreous Detachment. It was previously reported to Pfizer when he got the diagnosis of the PVD and all the events mentioned were previously reported. Reporter stated that from that day on the floaters got larger; the around 15Mar2021 he noticed every time he bent over he saw streaks of lightning; and he started to have a black hole, a loss of about 20% of his field of vision in the left eye. He went to another local optometrist 19Mar2021, who saw a large horseshoe tear in on left retina; and a detached left retina. The local optometrist sent him to a specialist and who verified the tear and the detachment and said the other retina in the right eye also has a small tear. Patient then had eye surgery, Monday at 0700AM, 22Mar2021 by outpatient surgery, to drain the fluid in his eye; insert a gas bubble and a silicone band to repair the retina; and did laser surgery on the tear. The specialist advised that the surgery damages the lens so he will need the lens replaced in the future. Now her patient has to lay down with his face down for 23 hours a day for two weeks and take 6-8 weeks off work. He had a doctor's visit yesterday and the doctor seemed satisfied with his progress but he can't see out of the eye, everything was cloudy so he doesn't know if the floaters are gone or the eye sight is recovered yet. The doctor was planning to do the right eye tear repair on Thursday 25Mar2021. Reporter had searched online to see if other people have this, but she can't seem to get the stories online about problems with the retina and the vaccine. She wanted this to be known and documented. Reporter was asking if company have information about if other people have had this. As per reporter, the events were not serious. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the events reported. The patient required physician's office visit for the events reported. The patient had not recovered from section of vision lost in the left eye, large left horseshoe tear on the retina in the left/tear on the right retina/small tear right eye, detached retina on the left, and floaters. The outcome of the other events reported was unknown.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Eye operation (He already had surgery once.)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the 1st dose of Moderna COVID vaccine lot # 041B21A, expiration date 5/6/21 at 12PM. At 12:03PM, EMTs  received a report from client that she was feeling dizzy, mild headache and a little shaky.  Vitals were taken-blood pressure:140/90, pulse:91 and oxygen 99%.  PHN came to find client sitting upright in chair, alert and oriented x4, able to provide medical history of hypertension. Client reports she has never had any reactions to any vaccine. Client medication is Telmisartan and client reports taking her medication this morning and that her blood pressure is usually 120/80 when taking medication. Client reports to PHN that she is feeling more dizzy, PHN and EMTs transfer client to gravity chair. Offer client water and offer to call 9-1-1, patient declines and calls husband.  At 12:09pm  client reports feeling cold and shakiness is worse. Cover client with disposable blanket. Another nurse joined to assist. At 12:11PM vitals were taken oxygen 98%, blood pressure: 146/78 and pulse: 85. At 12:16PM client drank half a bottle of water and reports dizziness improving and no shortness of breath.  PHN educate client about speaking to provider about reaction and discussion about next dose. Client also reports headache is better and able to have a conversation. At 12:17PM retake vitals blood pressure: 158/100, oxygen:96%, and pulse:83. client reports headache is worse, no chest pain, no blurred vision, no dizziness reported. At 12:23PM vitals taken-blood pressure 160/84, oxygen 98% and pulse 71. Client alert and oriented x 4 and still feeling cold. Client reports feeling chest pain and dizziness, PHN called 911 at 12:26PM.  At 12:29PM client reports feeling numbness in both of her legs-pulse, motor, sensation intact in both legs, alert and oriented x 4, client reports no shortness of breath. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Administered Janssen COVID-19 vaccine to pt and had him sit in designated chairs for monitoring. A couple of minutes later he said he was feeling light-headed. We had him stay seated in the chair and I went and got the BP machine. I had the technician taking notes. Checked BP and it was 67/35 pulse 75. I advised him that we will have him lie down and elevate his feet to help increase his BP but he declined and stated that this usually happens with needles. I checked his BP again and it was 79/28 pulse 71. We gave him a bottle of water and very shortly after he expressed he was feeling much better. At no point did the patient have trouble breathing or was experiencing any symptoms of allergic reaction/anaphylaxis. I had patient stay seating for another 10 minutes and checked his BP one last time and it had come up to 110/77 pulse 79 and he expressed he was feeling back to normal.

RASH AT INJECTION SITE (dose 1 and 2) DOSE 1: I noticed a 3in diameter rash around the injection site of my vaccine on *day six or seven*. It was hot to the touch, itchy and sore to the touch. It lasted for seven to nine days, but did not lead me to seek medical treatment. DOSE 2: I noticed a 3in diameter rash around the injection site of my vaccine on *day two*. It was hot to the touch, itchy and sore to the touch. It lasted for seven to nine days, but did not lead me to seek medical treatment.  VAGINAL ULCER (dose 2 only) I had a 5mm diameter ulcer on the inside of my left labia minora. I began having pain two days after my vaccine, where it felt uncomfortable to wear underwear or tight pants, but it wasn't until the morning of the fourth day that I investigated the pain and saw the ulcer.  I went to a local urgent care in the afternoon of the fourth day, where the nurses took a surface swab of the ulcer, drew blood for an STD panel, and performed a Pap smear. I was given one week worth of valacyclovir, an antibiotic (which I do not remember the name of), and fluconazole to prevent a (or treat a possible) yeast infection.  I took one dose of valacyclovir the evening of the fourth day and the morning of the fifth day with no apparent improvement. I did not take any additional doses, as it was recommended by my provider that if it was not effective within 24 hours, then it may not be effective at all.  I took all doses of the antibiotic and fluconazole.  I began to see improvements (reduced pain, shrinking size) by the seventh day. The ulcer disappeared completely by the twelfth day.
LAB_DATA: RASH AT INJECTION SITE None.  VAGINAL ULCER I had a surface swab of the ulcer, blood drawn for an STD panel, and a Pap smear on February 27, 2021. Results came back March 3, 2021 completely clear (no STDs, inconclusive swab, and unassuming Pap). I do not have a copy of the results, as they were relayed to me over the phone.

The next morning, 09:00 am, I had mild flu symptoms which was full body aches and feeling feverish and unwell. I didn't register a fever on the thermometer. I was very tired; no appetite. I stayed resting all day. Slept a lot. It was easy for me to sleep - very unusual. By 9:00 pm that all lifted and I was feeling back to normal. The morning of March 28, I woke up with a very sore throat. And on 3/29, I had really continued sore throat on and off and Tuesday it got much worse. There was a really strange sensation of being extremely thirsty - I had never had experienced that before. Swollen gland on the right side of my throat - between the jaw and ear area. I had a little bit of an earache on the right side. I drove by the drive-in testing area. I am working in person each day so I get the drive by testing - I think Tuesday, the 30th. Called the dr and did the Telehealth visit - Wednesday - the 31st. I had in and out of laryngitis - raspy voice and headache. I looked in my throat with flashlight and could see a definitive red spot in back of throat and some white spots.  They said it could be a blocked salivary gland and told me to eat something very sour to activate it. Over 6 to 8 hours it did clear the issue somewhat - thirst went away. I still had a sore throat. They told me that by the weekend, I could maybe start antibiotic. Saturday night I took first dose of Zpack - two tablets at first dose and then one tablet a day after that. By late evening Sunday (Easter) I felt some relief of symptoms. This week I still have a little bit of raspy voice and post nasal drip and clearing my throat at this point. I am recovering but not fully recovered.
LAB_DATA: Tuesday, the 30th, COVID PCR test  - Quest Diagnostics 0 result - negative (got the result Wednesday the 31st).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the COVID vaccine (Janssen, Lot# 1808980) complained of feeling dizzy at 1424, EMT  and RN responded. The client was sitting in a chair with her head in her hands, stated that she felt dizzy and was having a "hot flash." The client stated that she is anxious around needles and has a history of syncope after blood draws. She also complained of experiencing tunnel vision and hearing. The client's vital signs were a temperature of 96.7, blood pressure of 122/82, heart rate of 92, and O2 of 99%. The client stated she did eat that morning, and refused a set of repeat vitals, but agreed to wait 30 minutes for observation after her symptom onset. Per the client, she has no allergies or medical conditions, and takes no medications. At 1435, the client accepted some water to drink. At 1440, the client stated that she no longer felt dizzy. The client's color had returned and she was no longer dizzy. She agreed to have repeat vital signs at this time: blood pressure of 118/82, heart rate of 90, respiratory rate of 16, and O2 99%. The client refused benadryl at this time. At 1454, the client's vital signs were as follows: blood pressure of 116/82, heart rate of 90, respiratory rate of 12, and O2 of 99%. The client stated that she felt "back to normal" and called her sister to drive her home. She was escorted to her car by the EMT, she ambulated with a steady gait. Education provided regarding emergency response, V-safe, and the importance of following up with a primary care provider.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The night of January 9th around 2330 I noticed that the left side of my face was acting a little funny.  As the night progressed into the morning I noticed that it was starting to get worse and my face was drooping. By the evening of January 10th the left side of my face was really droopy. I had heard that a small percentage of the new COVID-19 vaccines had caused Bell's Palsy in a small percentage of the clinical trial patients. I did some research on Bell's Palsy and found what to do in the event of an onset. I took Advil 2 to 3 times a day  for about a week and kept a close eye on it to make sure that it wasn't getting any worse. After about 2.5 to 3 weeks the symptoms of the Bell's Palsy went away on its own. I did not see any physicians for treatment.
OTHER_MEDS: Over the counter vitamin c, b-12, fiber.

About 3 mins after Janssen vaccine was given, pt was very white and faintish.  I rushed out of pharmacy and had a tech call 911.  As I was running to him pt started slipping out of his chair, as a women, who I later found out was his mother and I helped keep pt in chair as he fainted and then seized for about 2 seconds and then gained consciousness. Upon awakening pt said , what  just happened?" The mother answered "oh you just had a little seizure, you're fine." To my surprise, I asked the mother is this has happened before and she said yes when he sees needles/get shots.  I told them the ambulance was on it's why and the mother asked "why?!" I told her because your son just fainted/had a seizure and we want to make sure he is ok.  The pt refused to go to the hospital.  I did go back out there and mentioned to them that it is very important to answer questions truthfully any time they are asked as they failed to honestly answer our questions about ever feeling faint after receiving a vaccine. His blood pressure normalized and once the paramedics left so did they.

He verbalized ahead of time that he has a history of fainting due to his fear of needles.  He does not have any allergic reaction to vaccine components.  After reviewing his PQCF and possible side effects of the vaccine, patient verbally consented to get vaccinated.  I administered the vaccine into the deltoid muscle of his right arm.  I gave him an ice pack.  Right after the vaccine was administered patient said he felt fine.  He relocated from the immunization booth to a Post Vaccine waiting chair with his wife by his side.  He fainted into his wifes's arms for about 30 seconds.  His father-in-law helped place him on his back on the floor and we raised his legs up on a chair.  Patient came to immediately when placed on supine position and said he just needed to rest.  We called Code White and assistant manager came to the scene.  Patient was conscious and verbalized that he was feeling fine but should just rest.  Patient continued to use ice pack and rested for about 30 minutes.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Only symptom experienced during first ~36 hours after receiving vaccine was soreness near injection area of left arm.   A couple hours after falling as sleep the second night after vaccination shot (Sunday night), I woke up very cold / severe shivering. After several hours I managed to fall asleep for approximately another 1-2 hours. The next day I experienced fever, shivers, general body weakness/fatigue, and muscle aches/discomfort especially in both legs. These symptoms lasted throughout the day.  That night (Monday night), when I got into bed, I was strongly shivering. I managed to fall asleep for 1-2 hours, but woke up uncomfortably warm. I was unable to fall back asleep until 4-5 hours later. I woke up 1-2 hours later, with most of my body dripping with sweat, and the sheets rather damp.  Tuesday and Wednesday: Symptoms came and went, mostly feelings of fever, chills, general fatigue, lost appetite, and mild light headedness. Sleeping remained difficult, able to stay asleep for <4 hours each night.    As of today (Thursday), fever has subsided. Still generally feel fatigued, occasionally lightheaded.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 9 days after receiving my second dose of the Moderna vaccine, I woke up with my right ankle hurting. It was swollen and tender to touch. I tried NSAIDS, ice, and elevation initially. It was not getting better, so I went to see a physician on Friday (started on Monday). I was given an antibiotic and prescription NSAID that did not seem to help. I had red spots that looked like a rash with heat coming from the area (right lateral ankle). The swelling worsened and pain continued. I was initially treated for an infection, but then symptoms began on my left leg (medial ankle). Hypersensivity was present in both ankles/legs with weakness noted. I went to see my family doctor a week after symptoms started. Antibiotics and NSAIDs were stopped and I was placed on predisone. Prednisone helped fairly quickly but the swelling and some pain continues. Redness and heat from the areas is decreasing.
LAB_DATA: Blood draw completed on  April 2nd showing increased WBC count and neutrophil count. ANA came back positive a few days later. I received an x-ray of the R ankle which showed no significant findings.
OTHER_MEDS: Birth control pill, Zyrtec, Singulair, prenatal vitamins

The patient then became unconscious for approximately 10-15 seconds with small jerking movements identified during this time. 911 was called and the patient was monitored until EMS arrived. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccination appointment was at 1:30 pm on Monday, April 5. I received the shot at around 2:00pm in my left arm. It hurt going in, but quickly dissipated as I moved my arm. I felt fine for the rest of the day. I felt normal the following morning (April 6), but started to feel tired in the early afternoon. I took a nap around 3:00-4:30pm, and woke up feeling slightly hungry. I went to bed around 11:00pm. I woke up the next day (April 7) with a headache. I called in sick to work and stayed in bed as my headache grew worse and nausea began to appear. I threw up for the first time at 11:00am, then again around 11:30am. I emptied my bowels in between these bouts of vomiting, and my stomach was very obviously empty after the second bout. I took a nap from 12:00-2:00pm, after which I threw up at 2:30pm and then again at 3:00pm and again at 3:30pm. I took another nap from 4:00-5:00pm, then threw up again around 5:30pm. I threw up a seventh time around 6:00pm and saw  a couple flecks of blood in my vomit. Each bout was sudden in onset and violent but quick. I think I burst some of the blood vessels in my throat, because it was sore. I called a friend to take me to the ER, and threw up once or twice more while waiting. On the way to the ER, I threw up for the last time. The ER gave me Toradol, Zofran, and two bags of IV fluids. This improved all my symptoms. The next morning, April 8, I felt much better until 12:00pm, when I laid down for a nap and couldn't get out of bed until 4:30. My headache had returned so I took Advil, then ate some rice. I felt better from 6:00pm onwards.
LAB_DATA: All on April 7, 2021:  CBC w/Differential Comprehensive Metabolic Panel Lipase Magnesium level POCT Pregnancy Urine, Qualitative  All  results were normal

She had trouble breathing and some lightheadedness, but it was ruled to be an anxiety response as everything looked normal. Over the time spent in the clinic, the color began to become less intensely blue and fade back to a normal skin color -- but not completely. At about 7:30 PM, she got up to walk and started feeling pins and needles in her arm and upper chest, but this may be due to anxiety.   The feeling disappeared not long after, and we were able to make it home and eat. Everything else that night went OK, except for the fact that her hand is, at the time of this report, still blue-ish in color.

Tuesday 6 go the first Pfizer Covid vaccine at the race track. In the past I have had angioedema and breathing issues but never severe enough to warrant going to hospital with several injections and from over the counter meds and prescription meds. So I was wary but decided to risk a jab. Straight up got tingling tongue and lips but after 15 min was just dizzy and roughly the same feeling. I am a slow up taker and excreter though. By the time I got home, about 20 min after the 15 min wait my neck on the injection side and swelled so much I no longer had a jaw and my eyes and cheeks were pretty puffy. Then the breathing issue started. I called the gp who said Tylenol, benedryl. Usually have them made because I have problems with additives but i don?t have any right now. So I used two ea kids chewable which allow me to have a dosage that works for me as I am sensitive to larger doses which can cause pvcs. Things were better but not good enough so took Zyrtec 10 ml/24 hr. If I had not had a similar experience with other injections this would have completely freaked me out. Thank goodness my quick treatment worked well enough that I felt confident worse was unlikely to happen, though the gp and allergist both wanted me to go to the er. Yesterday I did a repeat of Tylenol and benedryl in the morning and Zyrtec in the afternoon at two pm then Tylenol and benedryl again in the evening as I still had angioedema and felt tight in breathing. Repeat benedryl and Tylenol today but no Zyrtec as felt good enough to ride stationary bike a very slow Five miles. As to fever and other typical symptoms it has been hard to tell what is reaction and what is simply the vaccine doing its job. I did not take my temperature but have felt hot no general malaise. I recognize my symptoms are unusual but felt you should have them.
LAB_DATA: None. I have dermatogrphia so skin tests will give poor results.
HISTORY: Off the top my head autoimmune inflammatory disease, ibs, HEDs, non defined lung disease.
PRIOR_VAX: Hives or angioedema swollen lips buzzing to gue
ALLERGIES: Food sensitivities: wheat, soy, preservatives, dyes,  salt, sugar, peanuts, brown potatoes, psillium, fats, I am sure there is more but can?t think right now.  Drug sensitivities: penicillin, amoxicillin, ampacillin, cephlex, cipro, sulfa, nsaids, levequin, steroids, morphine,. Antihistamines and Tylenol can cause pvcs in adult doses.

Half way there my tongue started to swell and my lips slightly with tingle. My breathing was more labored to keep up effort as I could not expand my lungs to capacity. I was always able to breath and speak, my voice did become more raspy.    Upon ER, Blood Pressure was very Hypertensive around 140s/120s with my respiratory effort to get in. Pulse was stable around 70-80. O2 was 97-99.  I was able to lay down and relax my breathing which relaxed my blood pressure to 140s/ 80s. I was given IV Benadryl, IV Dexadron, PO Pepcid with a liter of fluid. Monitor up until after 8pm when I was released with still mild tonge swelling but breathing ok. Continue Benadryl at home with my Epi pen for bees stings available.    Did go to work today 07/08/2021. Was wheezy, SOB, no throat swelling, tongue swelling at base. Kept up with Benadryl. Made it 1/2 day and went home. Walking and movement makes increase lung workload. My staff concerned with effort and flush skin while getting supplies. But flush and redness does subside some with rest. When talking need to take a break to breath. But can today notice when Benadryl kicks in. No history of Asthma ever or breathing issues ever. Very active on my farm and at work.

Dose received at 6:05PM. Patient was seated in waiting area and around 6:10PM a loud noise was made due to metal chairs moving in the waiting area; upon turning around patient was face down on the floor with his head turned to one side. I ran to offer assistance and cushioned his head with my hands. EMS was dispatched immediately. Patient was already starting to come to after losing consciousness for approximately 10-15 seconds, looked confused for about 15 seconds and then seemed to return to a normal mental state immediately after. He was able to give his name and info and knew exactly where he was, etc. and he stated he felt much better. He was able to confirm he hit the side of his head on the floor, however it was not bleeding. I asked if he wanted me to call anyone for him but refused the offer. His blood pressure was taken at 6:15PM by us then again when EMS arrived at approximately 6:20PM and was 140/100. He was checked out by EMS, including a blood glucose reading of 81 and seemed to be okay. They offered to take him via ambulance to the hospital, especially given him hitting his head, but he refused the offer. He explained a similar incident occurred when he received IV contrast dye in the past. He was able to sit up and then stand up without any issues. He continued to wait in the waiting area for about 10 more minutes before leaving to ensure he felt back to normal. I followed up with him at 8:20PM via telephone and he stated he was feeling normal and had no questions/concerns. I assured him he could reach back out to me personally or the store here if he had any questions/concerns in the future.

I received my second dose of the COVID19 Moderna on 4/2/21 @7:40  through my employer, where I've worked over 11 years. By that evening, I had the normal fatigue, headache, and sore arm at my injection site that evening which even became swollen, red, and rashy by that next morning with some joint pain but attributed to normal side effects and dismissed it. But I woke up early Sunday morning, 04:30, very sick, with a fever, chills, diarrhea, cramping and aching abdomen and joints and also developed a rash and hives on my arm, up my neck, into my hair and down my chest left chest with some swelling as well. I took some Benadryl, it went down some but continued but I called the Tele service line to be evaluated as my symptoms were getting worse, not better. I continued experiencing these side effects as they increased intensity, especially the watery diarrhea that occured almost immediately everytime I drank and the rash and hives and ache in joints. I lost all appetite and even got so nauseas it woke me from a 10 minute nap vomitingI had an appointment w/MD 04/06/2021where she prescribed Zofran and told me to take Imodium, which I did not think I could since I was told nothing but Tylenol after the vaccine.She told me to follow -up with my primary or ER if I wasn't better by Thursday, today, but didn't think my diarrhea and stomach had anything to do with my vaccine.My fever, chills, rash, hives and itchiness came back and continued throughout yesterday as soon as I tried to stop taking Benadryl and Tylenol for a day as my stomach was so upset, cramping and sore. I went online to request an appointment with my PMD for follow-up and further evaluation as I am still nauseous too, and as I discovered after trying to eat toast and rice again, my taste is off.I received no response to my requests online so I called my doctors office today and they made a special appointment by telephone @08:30pm with Dr. so I do not have to come into the Clinic and get others sick.I've had to submit a LOA claim as well from missing now what will be 5 days of work. I hoping to be better soon.
LAB_DATA: None yet, follow up appointment tomorrow.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received a Janssen COVID vaccine on 4/8/21 at around 5:00 pm.  The patient was nervous during the administration and reported never receiving a flu vaccine in the past.  The common side and serious side effects were discussed with the patient.  The vaccine was administered to the patient without issue.  The patient and husband instructed to wait 15 minutes after the administration of the vaccine as is the recommendation per the CDC.  About 5 minutes after the administration of the vaccine, the patient's husband notified the pharmacy staff that his wife was not felling well.  Pharmacist responded to the patient.  The patient reported shortness of breath and feeling hot and stated she was about to pass out.  Pharmacist was instructed to retrieve the Epi-Pen from the immunization cart and assist.  Code White was called and Division 1 staff responded and assisted.  The patient was lowered to the ground and her feet were elevated.  It was at this point that it was determined that the patient was not experiencing anaphylaxis based on the symptoms she was reporting and exhibiting.  The patient was instructed to remove mask to help obtain better breaths and remove the patient from hyperventilation.  An icepack was obtained and placed on the patients neck once she was able to sit up.  The patient's symptoms improved to the point of moving to a chair.  The patient sipped water and continued deep breathing.  The patient's symptoms continued to improve and she was able to leave.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got the vaccine at around 11am on 6th April.  By 8pm the same day I was experiencing very severe chills - I have never felt so cold before in my life,  and the evening was not cold..  The next day, 7th April,  I woke up with bad aches in various, seemingly random areas of my body:  both upper arms, outside parts of both thighs, center of back between shoulder blades.  Interestingly all the aches were symmetrical.  I had not done any serious exercise to cause these symptoms, just a stroll around the park after getting the vaccine. I also experienced crushing tiredness and had to go back to bed in the afternoon.  Today, 8th April at 5:30 pm my left arm at the vaccine site still aches, but all the other symptoms had vanished by the morning.  I'm 5' 4" and weigh 114lbs.  My husband got the vaccine at the same time and had no symptoms.  We are speculating that my smaller size may have contributed to my adverse reaction.  He is 5' 6" and weighs 180lbs.  In spite of this discomfort I'm so relieved and pleased that we were able to get the vaccine.  Thank you!

By 5 hours after the injection my muscles were cramping or slightly spasming, my skin felt bruised or like it was sunburned, and any contact, even with clothing was incredibly uncomfortable. The next morning I felt better, though I still had muscle/joint aches, until about 1 in the afternoon, so about 17 hours after the injection, when I became very tired. Event took place at an off-site event, in a detention facility. Pt received Janssen COVID vaccine around 4:00 pm. Pt immediately reported nausea. Nurse accompanied pt to the restroom about 2 minutes after receiving vaccine, where she gagged into the sink and spit up a little clear fluid. Pt reported feeling hot and sat down in a chair available in the restroom. Pt and nurse joined by a second nurse. Shortly after sitting down pt complained of feeling dizzy and was moved to the floor to lay down. When laying down, pt appeared flushed under her chin and complained of chest tightness. She requested to sit up to help with breathing. Called 911 and first dose of epinephrine (0.5 mL of 1mg/1mL) administered, both at 4:10 pm. Pt reported no change in chest tightness following epi, but continued to respond to questions. She said she felt tired and wanted to go to sleep. Pt continued to report difficulty breathing, and another dose of epinephrine administered at 4:15 pm. A physician at GEO arrived and administered oxygen. He listened to pt's heart and lungs and reported that there was air movement in her lungs. Pt ceased to respond coherently to questions, slurring and moaning, but did not lose consciousness. Pt started tapping her lips and, upon questioning, said they felt numb. Third dose of epinephrine administered at 4:20 pm. Nurse continued to jostle patient and ask her questions, and patient continued to respond with short, slurred answers. EMS arrived at 4:23 pm and transported patient to the hospital.
ALLERGIES: Pt reported history of anaphylaxis to oral aspirin.

I also have overall weakness and doing basic tasks like writing essays for school has become painful and difficult. My hand is stiff and looks like a claw. While it has gotten a little better after taking medications that my doctor prescribed my fingers are still weak stiff, numb, tingling, and painful.  The vaccine was administered too far up and too far to the left which has most likely caused nerve damage.  There is also a small bruise at the injection site and the injection is still visible 5+ days later. This could have been prevented through better training of health officials working at state-run vaccine sites. I hope this hasn't caused lasting damage.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient stated he started to feel unwell a few minutes after the vaccine, then started to feel light headed, nauseous, dizzy. He reported he felt like he was about to pass out, he felt he had dry mouth and was thirsty. To provider he appeared pale and sweating. He was instructed to sit in chair and lean forward with head down towards knees. He was provided water and his blood pressure was taken. The first reading was 89/66 pulse 74. He stated he was not sure what his normal pressure was, but was usually low. He also stated that he had a light breakfast, and didn't really drink much that day. After his pressure was taken he reported to feel slightly better, and was observed for another 25-30 minutes. After this time passed, his blood pressure was taken again, and reading was 102/74 and his color appeared better, and was more alert. After a few more minutes, he said he felt much better. He also had eaten crackers at this time. He was provided v-safe form again, and encouraged to sign up for follow-up, and to continue to monitor closely any symptoms for at least the next 6 hours.

The night after my second Pfizer vaccine on 4/6/2021, I didn?t sleep well. I was tossing and turning all night. I started getting a bad headache. By the time I woke up on 4/7/2021, I felt like when you?re coming down with the flu- I had a really bad headache, my whole body hurt, and I was exhausted. I had a loss of appetite that day. I was able to sleep for 3 hours later that day, woke up, took Advil, and felt mostly better. I slept good the night of 4/7/2021, and after waking up on 4/8/2021, I felt much better. I still had mild muscle aches and a slight headache. At work I felt like I had some brain fog but by the evening of 4/8/2021, I felt completely back to normal. I knew these were expected side effects of the vaccine due to my immune system doing it?s job. I did not need to make any calls to my doctor or hospital.

About 72 hours after her 2nd Moderna vaccine, patient developed an uncommon condition known as Lipschutz ulcers. It is a non sexually transmitted condition characterized by the rapid onset of painful, necrotic ulcerations of the vulva or lower vagina.  Pt presented with moderate unilateral labial swelling, several vulvar ulcers noted to inner labia minora with yellow/bloody discharge. Some ulcers with necrotic appearing tissue. Extremely tender to touch. Pt without hx of EBV infection.
LAB_DATA: 4/1/21 Genital wound culture, GC/CT culture, vaginitis culture. Treated with Bactrim, Motrin 600mg for pain, sitz bath, topical lidocaine  5% for pain. Follow up planned for 4/5/21 4/5/21 Slight improvement in pain, necrotic area no longer noted to ulcerated lesions. Using lidocaine TID, labial swelling decreased. Continue Motrin. Cultures pending.  4/6/21 Returned to office due to moderate pain, inability to sleep through the night. Placed on Tramadol 50mg. Labs ordered: CBC, HSV titers. HSV culture done.  4/7/21 Would culture positive for Klebsiella. Moderate labial swelling persists. Severe pain persists. Moderate yellow discharge increasing. Started on oral steroids and Cipro.  CMP, EBV titers added to bloodwork.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Onset variety of symptoms approximately 3/29, 10 days after 2nd covid vaccine: fever, chills swelling in his axilla, ear pain and discharge, headache, body/joint aches.  Seen in clinic 3/31 and treated with augmentin for otitis, which he took with some improvement but return of drainage 3 days later.  Intermittent urinary discomfort, which improved briefly then returned and culminated in passage of a small amount of blood. Was seen in ED for that, and confirmed to have RBC in urine, but CT abd/pelvis negative, CBC normal. Was told evaluation normal but may need to see urology. He thinks may have passed small kidney stone.  Ten days later, continues with fevers (subjective - has no thermometer), chills, body aches, joint pain, headaches.  Axillary swelling has decreased in size but he feels a pain deeper inside at that area. Pain & fever improve with tylenol but both return when it wears off. No further urinary symptoms.  No rashes No recent travel Feels a little pressure in his chest to breathe, but no difficulty breathing.  Never had cough No contact with COVID positive (or suspected positive) person - has only been at home.  Was offered COVID test in ED but declined due to did not feel he was at risk of having come in contact with it.
LAB_DATA: CBC, BMP normal; CT abd/pelvis with no acute findings.  Arranging now for COVID test and for further evaluation in clinic.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Female patient (44 years old)  came to COVID-19 Clinic on 04-08-2021. Patient reported she does not have severe reactions to food, pet environmental, oral medications. After 15 minutes, patient started to have adverse reactions such as severe diaphoresis and fatigue. The pharmacy team instructed the patient to lay down on the floor with legs elevated. After 10 minutes, patient reported in better condition. The pharmacy team  reconfirmed if the patient has other allergic reactions to other medications., patient now mentioned the allergies list. such as contract dye (rapid heart beat), erythromycin, bactrim, keflex (severe dehydration. nausea, vomiting)  However, the vaccine coordinator contacted 911 while the pharmacy assisting the patient. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient (DOB 4/19/1991)  received the COVID vaccine at 1405. At 1407, she reported dizziness and EMT and RN  responded. She complained of lightheadedness and was clammy and pale. Vital signs were as follows: heart rate of 112, respiratory rate of 12, and O2 of 99%. The client has no allergies, takes no medications, and has no medical conditions that she is aware of. She was alert and oriented, and her pupils were equal and reactive to light. At 1415, the client had another set of vitals taken: blood pressure 100/palpable, heart rate 102, and O2 99%. The client was unable to keep her arm still and stated the blood pressure cuff was too tight, so the blood pressure was difficult to obtain. The client refused water at this time and stated her last meal was at 1330. At 1420, the client stated she felt more calm and EMT attempted a repeat blood pressure, which was 104/60. At this time, the client's color had returned and she was less clammy. At 1425, the client's repeat vital signs were as follows: blood pressure of 100/80, heart rate of 104, respiratory rate of 16, and O2 of 98%. The client was again offered water, which she refused. At 1430, the client stated that she would rate the severity of her symptoms at an 8/10 and she was now rating her symptoms of dizziness and lightheadedness at 2-3/10. At this time, the client accepted a bottle of water and started to drink it, no complaints of nausea. At 1435, the client's repeat blood pressure was 110.80 band her heart rate was 100. She stated her symptoms were resolved. Benadryl was refused. At 1442, the client's vital signs were as follows: her blood pressure was 108/82, heart rate of 98, respiratory rate of 14 and an O2 of 98%. The client was educated regarding system, emergency response and when to activate , and to follow up with her primary care provider. The client was escorted out to her car by EMT , ambulating with a steady gait, and was driven home by her girlfriend.

16:03: Vaccine Administered 16:13 Patient received there 2nd COVID vaccine and was monitored. After 10 minutes the patient demonstrated that she started the" I feel different, I am having tingling in my throat and it feels very different then it did before." She reported feeling dizzy and nauseous. She declined lying down. Pts vital signs were obtained HR 104, 99% O2, BP 138/88. Pt was given a sip of water and advised that she would remain in the clinic for additional monitoring. I advised the I could administer an Epi-pen and call the paramedics which she stated she didn't want at this time as she has never needed something like that before.   1633 - Patient was reassessed for vitals 132/88 BP, 99% O2 and 87 HR. Pt stated that she feels like her tongue is weird maybe swollen and it still feels weird to swallow, she isn't anxious but has a bit of a groggy mental haze. She stated that she feels weaker then usual and has a pressure in her head. I called Dr. and got permission to administer 25mg of Diphenhydramine orally. Pt stated that she has taken this medication before and that she will be safe to drive after taking this medication. Pt was advised that she would be monitored for another 20 minutes to ensure that the medication kicks in and symptoms start to resolve.   16:52pm 132/92 BP, 99% O2, 88HR. Hoarse voice, scratchy throat tongue is improving doesn't feel as swollen. Pt was evaluated by Dr.  17:26 Patient was discharged and advise to closely monitor her symptoms for the next 3 hours.   I received a call saying that patient was having some tingling in her lips and tongue and slight nausea. She was given 25 mg oral Benadryl by the RN. The patient was monitored for approximately an hour with serial vital signs. I briefly assessed this patient. She reports feeling some tingling in her lips with improvements in tingling in her tongue. She also reports feeling warm. Patient states that her throat feels scratchy and she feels like she has to clear her throat. Her heart sounds were normal and she has a normal respiratory effort and lungs clear to auscultation. No tongue swelling or posterior oropharynx swelling. Posterior oropharynx is pink and moist. Patient was advised that she is most likely having a reaction to the COVID vaccine. Patient should continue to monitor her symptoms at home. Patient states there will be someone at home with her. Patient was advised if she has any worsening symptoms such as tongue swelling, shortness of breath, chest pain, palpitations, body wide rash or throat swelling that she should report to the emergency department or call 911. Patient is advised that she can take another Benadryl. She was given 25 mg of Benadryl around 4:00 PM. Patient is advised that if her symptoms do worsen she can take another 25 mg of oral Benadryl in the next four hours. If she is on her way to the hospital or waiting for an ambulance she should take another Benadryl. Patient was also advised to take over-the-counter allergy medicine such as Claritin or Zyrtec for a couple of days. She is to call the clinic with any questions. Patient verbalizes understanding and has no further questions.
OTHER_MEDS: trazodone, phentermine, vit b-12 and Vit D

LAB_DATA: At the emergency room on 4/4/21 I was given a CAT scan to rule out bleeding in the brain. Bloodwork was done and platelet count was 8,000. I was  confined to a bed and told I was too high risk to walk, as a fall or even the slightest injury could have been catastrophic. I  have never had any blood disorders in the past or issues prior. I was admitted to the hospital and diagnosed with ITP (Acute Thrombocytopenia). I was given 3 platelet transfusions each lasting 2.5 hours and two rounds of immunoglobulin (4 hours each round). Steroid 40mg a day for 4 days. I was in the hospital until Wednesday the 7th. When I was released my platelet levels were back up to 69,000 still a long way from normal. I still have to go in every couple days for bloodwork to monitor platelet levels.

She was able to answer questions like "what is your name?" "where are your?" " etc. She denied a history of fainting but did say she fainted once about 8 years ago.  She remained seated in the pharmacy waiting area for another 30 minutes and said she felt fine. She denied feeling dizzy, short of breath, and any allergic reaction symptoms.

Client received the COVID vaccine (Moderna, lot # 041AB21A) at 1005. Client reported dizziness, and EMT, Nurse  and Physician all responded at 1010. The client was sitting in his chair, head back with his eyes closed. The client stated that he was going to pass out and he appeared very pale and diaphoretic. The client was transferred to the reclining chair. At 1015, the client's vital signs were as follows: blood pressure of 110/68, heart rate of 78, respiratory rate of 16, and O2 99%. At 1020, the client stated he was "starting to feel better" and his vital signs were as follows: O2 99%, heart rate 59, and respiratory rate of 16. His color had improved to normal. The client refused benadryl. At 1025, the client's heart rate was 58, respiratory rate was 18, and O2 was 98. He stated he had no medical history, takes no medications, and has no allergies. At 1030, the client's blood pressure was 114/74. He was given a water which he started to drink. At 1040, the client's blood pressure was 112/70, with a heart rate of 57 abd O2 of 98%. The client stated his symptoms were completely resolved and he was able to stand without any return of dizziness. Education was provided regarding V-safe, emergency measure and activation, and primary care follow up. The client has no PCP so information was provided regarding. The client was escorted out to his car, ambulating with a steady gait, and he drove himself home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 7 hours from vaccine, my heart started palpitating and I started feeling sick. I got in my car to go home from a friends house and started severe chills and called Doctor for fear of heart attack. They told me to go to ER. I continued driving home. Chills got worse. I got in shower with heater on and chills persisted. Drank coconut water and heart palpitations resided.  Got in bed and fever spiked to 102 and every bone was inflamed in pain. Nyquil did nothing. After a few hours of severe and unbearable pain I called ER. Headed over to ER at 3:00 a.m. and sat in parking lot. Fever broke at 3:00 a.m. which was hour 14 after vaccine. Other than severe nausea, pain calmed down. Drove home with Tylenol. Took 1,000 mg and finally rested at 4:00 a.m. Woke up at 8:00 a.m. with nausea but pain gone. 24 hours from vaccine, most of the reaction gone. 48 hours out body normal but pain in injection site.
LAB_DATA: I did not enter ER, just waited outside. No medical tests done.
OTHER_MEDS: Synthroid, Estradiol, Progesterone, Amitriptyline. Tons of multi-vitamins, collagen, extra Vit D, C, etc.
CUR_ILL: none. Great health other than dealing with chronic cough.
HISTORY: No thyroid. 3 year chronic cough that was worsened by COVID in February 2020

Patient states right after he received the vaccine he developed difficulty swallowing, "I can't even eat anything, it just won't go down - the only thing I can eat is pudding." States his tongue has been "double the size it should be" since he received the covid vaccine. No worse today than it has been, "just not getting better and I still can't eat." No speech difficulties during conversation (enunciating words properly). Pt is now c/o difficulty breathing, "I just feel short of breath." States he noticed the SOB yesterday, worse today. +CP with both cough and deep inspiration. Some mild wheezing, chills. Cough is nonproductive. No conversational dyspnea or cough during conversation. Recommended local ER now, states he will have family member drive him to ER now.

Narrative:  65yr male with a history of CLL (stable disease on most recent CT) followed by Hematology service and was on observation without active treatment. PLT prior to Moderna #1 (2/19/21) and Moderna #2 (3/19/21) was WNL (238, date 1/27/2021). Within 2 days of Moderna #2 reports to hematology bleeding easily and PLT count was obtained <2 (3/24/21). Patient was directly admitted to the hospital for ITP (common CLL complication though one case report of IPT post vaccination). Bone marrow biopsy done on 3/31/21 showed 40% CLL cells with low normal megakaryocytes on preliminary read. ITP Therapy: Continues on prednisone 1mg/kg, s/p IVIG 3/25-3/28, rituximab-pvvr on 4/1 (4 weekly doses) started MMF and TXA 650mg TID on 4/2 for ongoing mucosal bleeding and low PLT (<2), then eltrombopag 50mg daily started on 4/3 (PLT <2). PLT count on 4/6 <2 and Surgical team consulted for consideration of splenectomy. On 4/7 PLT 5000 ITP is refractory to steroids and IVIG, with ongoing severe thrombocytopenia on rituximab, MMF, eltrombopag. Surgical Consult: ITP in light of multiple medical treatments, a laparoscopic, possible open, splenectomy is warranted. Surgery is planned for 7:30AM on Thursday, 4/8/2021.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: HEART ATTACK (Heart attack, Myocardial infarction) HIGH FEVER (Fever, Pyrexia) This spontaneous report received from a patient concerned an adult male. The patient's height, and weight were not reported. The patient's past medical history included aortic valve repair, and aortic valve replacement, and concurrent conditions included heart disorder.   The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin, and batch number were not reported) dose was not reported, administered on 10-MAR-2021 12:30 for prophylactic vaccination. The batch number was not reported and has not been requested. No concomitant medications were reported. On 10-MAR-2021 at 19:30, the patient unexpectedly broke out into a very cold sweat, high fever, extreme stomach nausea, and his heart raced to levels he had never felt. The patient could not walk and could barley respond verbally to his fianc� for help. The patient was admitted to the hospital. The patient was taken on a wheelchair and was attended to immediately because of the severity of his condition. The emergency room doctors and nurses thought the patient was having a heart attack, as did he. The patient informed emergency room doctors and nurses that he had been given covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s earlier in the day. After several hours of testing including electrocardiogram, computerized tomography scans, intravenous and constant blood pressure monitoring, it was determined that the patient should be transported to a hospital that was better equipped to service his apparent condition. Patient further states that he had an EKG, MRI, Nuclear stress test, CAT Scan and a Transesophageal ECHO, all of which "came back ok". He stated that there was also concern for brain damage, which was eventually ruled out. Patient states that he has no new additional diagnoses. He denies any current cardiac diagnoses or disorders. He spent 2 days in the hospital at 2 different facilities for testing and evaluation. He states that there were no other medications taken on the day or at the time of vaccination. He adds that there was no exposure to COVID-19. Reporter states that he had been tested twice for the virus for and upcoming flight/travel. He also added that he was also tested again at the hospital, all test were negative. He also added that he was also tested again at the hospital, all tests were negative. He also added that he had no other recent The hospital staff was concerned about a possible heart attack and not knowing the patient's history or having the equipment and staff to service this, they decided the past for "born-in" heart issues, the patient wanted to be transported to Medical Center where all of his doctors were residences. According to the patient, they had a fabulous team of world renowned cardiology experts from Cardiology. The hospital staff offered to send the patient to another General hospital. Both hospitals were about equal distance from original facility. The patient obviously wanted to go to where his doctors were and who know him personally for almost his whole life. According to the patient, the staff the hospital were fantastic, and as they stated to him verbally, probably saved his life. An ambulance ride followed at about 3:00AM on 11-MAR-2021 arrived at approximately 04:30 at Medical Center. The patient's cardiologist's covering doctors met him on the cardiology floor to immediately begin monitoring and performing every test at their disposal. The patient also informed the cardiology team at Medical Center that he had received the Covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s vaccine on 10-MAR-2021 (Wednesday) afternoon. According to the patient, their eyes lit up immediately believing that the vaccine might had caused this. After almost 2 days and countless tests, blood screens, monitoring and consultation, the patient was released late afternoon on 12-MAR-2021 from hospital after being stabilized to a normal level. According to the patient's doctors, the only cause of these events could have been the Covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s vaccine. According to the patient, visits and the almost 2 day stays. The patient's doctors had instructed him to stay close to home and continue to monitor his condition in the upcoming weeks because no one knows if these events could happen again.  The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient recovered from heart attack, and high fever on 12-MAR-2021. This report was serious (Hospitalization Cause / Prolonged).  Additional information was received from patient on 26-MAR-2021. The following information was updated and incorporated into the case: Age group, age at the time of vaccination, medical history (aortic valve repair, and aortic valve replacement), lab test updated. Upon review, the follow information was amended: Seriousness criteria Other medical important condition removed for event Heart attack.

Pt is alert oriented to self, time, date  and location. Initial vital signs was taken by RN at 07:00 PM and it was 145/110mmhg, PR 138 ppm, RR20 cpm, Temp 98.1, Oxygen saturation of 99% at room air. RN assisted pt to lay patient down safely. No SOB and chest pain noted. Pt stated feeling better upon laying down for couple of minutes and stated that her dizziness comes and goes. Pt had no allergic reactions to any other vaccination but pt also stated that she has been feeling dizzy couple of times as her history. No history of elevated BP as well was stated by pt. Pt continuous to complain on and off dizziness, NP assess pt and Called 911 for further assistance. Repeat vitals check done by RN  BP 135/100 mmhm, PR 81 ppm, RR 20 cpm, oxygen saturation 98% at room air. EMT came at 07:45 PM came assess pt, checked her vitals, pt requested if she could walk and have the EMT assist her to evaluate herself, no complaints of dizziness reported. EMT offered to bring pt to hospital for further evaluation, pt refused to go to hospital. Pt was advised to go to hospital if episode of dizziness happens again. EMT walked the pt to her car and have her sister drive. Pt left facility at 08:00 PM without any complaints. VAERS was filed and education provider RN was reported.

Client received the COVID vaccine (Moderna, 1st dose,  lot #041AB21A, exp. 5/6/2021) at 1527. EMT observed the client to be pale and diaphoretic; he and RN responded at 1532. The client complained of dizziness, feeling clammy, and ringing in his ears, as well as spotty vision. His vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 96/78, heart rate 50, respiratory rate 20, and O2 99%. The client stated that he has hypertension and he takes losartan. He takes no other medications, has no other medical conditions, and has no allergies that he is aware of. The client was alert and oriented, and his pupils were equal and reactive to light. He stated that he ate breakfast and a snack at 11 am, but nothing for lunch. The client was offered water. At 1536, the client complained of tingling in his arms and numbness in his tongue. His color had returned to normal. No difficulty breathing, no swelling observed around his mouth or tongue, no complaint of metallic taste. Repeat vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 110/80, heart rate 87, O2 99%. He refused benadryl. At 1541, the client stated that his tongue was no longer numb but his arms were still tingling. He was less diaphoretic. His vital signs were as follows: blood pressure of 116/82, heart rate of 92, respiratory rate 14, and O2 97%. At 1545, the client stated he was no longer dizzy and his symptoms had resolved. Education provided regarding, emergency response and AMR activation, and primary care follow up. At 1550, the client was able to stand up and walk without any dizziness or feeling lightheaded. At 1558, the client's repeat vital signs were as follows: blood pressure 140/99, heart rate 99, respiratory rate 16, and O2 97%. The client was escorted outside by the EMT, and stated he was walking across the parking lot to get some food to eat before returning home. The client left the facility ambulating with a steady gate.

At 12 hours through 16 hours after administration of the vaccine I experienced rigorous shivers, feeling freezing cold to the bone for hours and couldn't get warm (even with piles of blankets), periodic heart pain and some chest pressure, periodic knife like stabbing pain in my right knee, mild nausea, dizziness, lightheadedness, severe weakness, sometimes a cough.  At 16 hours I got up to get water and had to hold onto things to keep my balance. After drinking a couple of cups of water, I turned away from the bathroom sink and lost consciousness, fainting and falling onto my bathroom floor. The jolt of the fall woke me up and it took a lot of strength to get up. The symptoms were vicious. When I fainted, the brunt of my weight must of been on my upper left rib cage. My ribs were so sore for a week. It was difficult to walk, breath, blow my nose, or cough.  My health provider recommended a Tylenol regime for pain control so that I could take deep breaths and prevent pneumonia. I had a low grade fever of 99 degrees F for one to two days following the vaccine. During the week that followed I felt periodically very ill, had a constant headache for a day or two, and had extremely foggy thinking and sometimes confusion.  I was very fatigued all week long. I lost my appetite and have still not gained my typical appetite back. Day 8 to 9 is when I was finally feeling closer to normal. Today I feel I may be back to 100%, but my rib cage is still healing, either from a contusion, fracture, or break (likely a contusion).
LAB_DATA: No tests conducted but I did report this to doctor near the end of last week at a medical appointment for another matter.
OTHER_MEDS: Levothyroxine (75 mcg and 80 mcg per day alternating), QVAR-80 (80 mcg, 2 inhalations per day), vitamin C (2500 to 3000 mg per day), folic acid (800 mcg per day), estradiol (0.01%, 1 gram per week)

shingles; Information has been received regarding a case in litigation from a lawyer and refers to a patient of unknown age and gender.  No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. In or around 09-OCT-2014, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, route, lot # and expiration date was not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine (date not reported), the patient suffered a vesicular rash on the left abdomen with scattered lesions on the lateral surface with pain, itching, and burning, which was diagnosed as Shingles. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of patient's condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result, the patient had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of shingles was considered not recovered. The event was considered to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Fever; Weakness; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of fever in a adult patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The subject's past medical history included allogeneic stem cell transplantation.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On an unknown date, less than a week after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced fever (serious criteria hospitalization) and weakness (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the fever and weakness were unknown.   The reporter considered the fever and weakness to be possibly related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Fever; Weakness, in a patient of unspecified age and gender, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis.  The patient was a part of a single-center prospective observational cohort study that was conducted between December of 2018 and June of 2020 to evaluate the safety and reactogenicity of recombinant zoster vaccine (RZV) in adult allogeneic hematopoietic cell transplantation (HCT) recipients, including any effects on graft-versus-host disease (GVHD) occurrence or exacerbation given the presence of an adjuvant. The patient was more than or equal to 18-year-old at the time of allogenic HCT. The patient was between 9 to 24 months from time to transplant and was deemed appropriate for RZV by treating clinician. The patient did not have disease relapse prior to administration of the first dose of RZV vaccination(V1). No information on patient medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unknown date, the patient received 1 intramuscular dose (0.5 mL) of Shingrix (administration site unspecified, batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported. [In this study, Cohort A consisted of patients who received V1 at 9 to 12 months after transplant in accordance with a hospital vaccination guidelines. Cohort B consisted of patients who received V1 at 12 to 24 months after transplant as part of a "catch-up" vaccination effort. RZV was given alongside other vaccines in the vaccine schedule. Patients were followed until June of 2020 and for more than or equal to 30 days after final vaccination. The primary end points were safety and reactogenicity in the total vaccinated cohort (TVC), which included all participants who received more than or equal to 1 vaccine dose. The secondary end points included incidence and severity of GVHD in the TVC compared with historical controls and the incidence rates of HZ in the TVC and modified TVC (mTVC), which included only patients who received both doses of the vaccine. Adult Post Hematopoietic Cell Transplant Vaccine Guidelines included: 9 months vaccine as DTaP, HiB, IPV, Prevnar, Shingrix; 12 months vaccine as DTaP, HiB, IPV, Prevnar, Menactra, Twinrix, Shingrix; 14 months vaccines as Hep B, Menactra; 18 months vaccines as DTaP, HiB, IPV, Prevnar, Twinrix and 24 months vaccines as MMR, Pneumovax]. On an unknown date, 3 days after vaccination (V1), the patient was hospitalized for fever and weakness. [In this study, HZ cases were defined as (1) a new rash that was characteristic (unilateral, dermatomal, painful, vesicular) and that was documented as HZ by a treating clinician or (2) an atypical rash or suspected disseminated VZV infection that was confirmed by VZV culture, direct fluorescent antibody detection, polymerase chain reaction, or immunohistochemical staining on tissue specimen. Patients who had HZ within 30 days of vaccine 2 (V2) were excluded from the mTVC analysis. A sensitivity analysis was performed looking at follow-up only in individuals who discontinued antiviral prophylaxis. During the study period, there were 5 deaths; they were secondary to disease relapse and infection and were not considered related to vaccination]. The case was considered as serious due to hospitalization. Treatment was unknown. Outcome of the event was not reported. The events were considered as possibly related to vaccination. The authors commented "Two doses of RZV demonstrated safety and tolerability in allogeneic HCT without increased rates of chronic GVHD (cGVHD), relapse, or death, as well as overall low rates of breakthrough. Vaccines were co-administered with RZV in the majority of participants which may have led to a higher incidence of solicited AEs than if RZV was administered alone. Although there have been concerns related to potential immune-mediated disorders (pIMDs) with the use of the RZV novel adjuvant AS01B system, there was no increased incidence or severity of cGVHD observed in the subgroup that was vaccinated between 9 and 12 months compared with historical controls in the peri-vaccination 9 to 15-month period. This finding is in keeping with renal transplant recipients who did not experience higher rates of solid organ rejection21 and healthy adults who did not have increased pIMDs after RZV. Patients on immunosuppression during vaccination had a higher incidence rate ratios (IRR) of cGVHD in the peri-vaccination period compared with those not on immunosuppression; however, they also likely represent a cohort with a higher baseline risk for alloreactivity.". The authors concluded "In summary, among recipients of allogeneic HCT, RZV was safe, tolerable, and did not increase rates of GVHD. There were few breakthrough cases of HZ in this cohort; however, future RCTs are needed to determine vaccine efficacy.". This article is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction. This is 1 of the 6 valid cases reported in this literature article; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2021GSK065731:Same reporter
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Allogeneic stem cell transplantation

SYMPTOM_TEXT: he was having confusion /  he was in a fog/cloud all day  / confusion; fatigue /  went to bed early; a concerted effort to concentrate/ loss of concentration/ inability to focus/not quite tunnel vision / had to concentrate really hard / had to concentrate on everything / inability to concentrate; arm discomfort; he felt like he was in a fog; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of confusion in a 60-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Pfizer Covid 19 shot (1st shot received on 1st December 2020). Concomitant products included COVID 19 VACCINE PFIZER.   On 1st April 2021, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. In April 2021, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced confusion, fatigue, concentration loss, arm discomfort and foggy feeling in head. On an unknown date, the outcome of the confusion, fatigue, concentration loss, arm discomfort and foggy feeling in head were recovered/resolved.   The reporter considered the confusion, fatigue, concentration loss, arm discomfort and foggy feeling in head to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were reported as follows: The patient reported the case for himself.  He got the shot around 6 pm at a local pharmacy.  He did not experience any immediate problems during or shortly after the injection.  No problems that evening. He went to bed.  He woke up in the middle of the night due to left arm discomfort.  He woke up the next morning at his regular time.  He proceeded with his normal routine of drinking coffee and going to the pool to swim.  During his swimming he stated that he felt like he was in a fog.  He said that he really had to concentrate on swimming which was unusual because he swims every morning and normally did not have to think about it as he performs this routine task.  He described it as a heavy fog, a concerted effort to concentrate or loss of concentration or inability to focus or not quite tunnel vision. Then as he was driving and the whole time while he was at work he had to concentrate really hard.  He said he had to concentrate on everything like he was having confusion and this lasted through his whole work day and he could not wait to go home.  He said he was in a fog or cloud all day Friday 2nd April 2021 with confusion, inability to concentrate and fatigue.  When he came home he went to bed early.  He woke up Saturday 03rd April 2021 and felt good.  He did not have a fever or a rash or gastrointestinal symptoms.  The reporter consented to follow up.

I got shingles 2 weeks after first dose. Doctors say get second dose 3 weeks later (today) but bc I have shingles I?m waiting a week or two. Listening to my two pharmacist friends and my gut/common sense. There are many people with my same story online who have gotten shingles after the first or second dose of the Covid vaccine. I don?t know how there can?t be a connection. My pharmacy?s and two doctors told me the vaccine lowers your immune system so it makes sense you would be more susceptible to getting shingles.    One pharmacist said this: The common thing is to wait till it?s gone before second dose because there have been no studies done with patients with shingles and so they say wait till it?s gone just to be safe. If you have active shingles, do not get vaccinated 2nd dose until healed. Even if it is past the 42 days, it?s still fine to get the next shot.  Another pharmacist said this: As of 4/8/21, the CDC does not state specifically that you cannot get the shot tomorrow due to taking valacyclovir or due to active shingles infection.  In my personal opinion,  If it were me I would wait until off the Valacyclovir and the shingles has gone away just to be sure your immune system is at full force. Hope that helps.
LAB_DATA: Saw a doctor/physician at Urgent Care on 4/6/21 and started in meds.
OTHER_MEDS: Daily:  Levothyroxine .100 mg Atorvastatin 80 mg (generic for Lipitor)  Losartan 50 MG  Triamterene 37.5 mg HCTZ (Hydrochlorothiazide) 25 mg Baby Aspirin 81 Mg Vitamin D Vitamin E Calcium Magnesium Temazapam 15 mg (try 7.5)

Began with severe back pain on 3/04/21. I went to the ER and they checked heart because pain radiated to front. I went home and pain continued briefly the next day. By 3/6, I began to have numbness in my left leg, so again, I went to ER and they  prescribed oral steroids and recommended MRI to be scheduled in back. My Monday 3/8 I was unable to walk and had no sensation from mid chest down. I could feel Pressure, but had no sense of temperature or sharpness. From that point I was admitted to the hospital. I spent a week on the 6th floor and a week on the inpatient rehab floor. They ruled out demyelinating disease that could cause  the lesion that was found on my cervical spine from c6-T-2. The records indicate demyelinating disease vs post vaccine reaction. All tests for demyelinating diseases came back negative, so it is believed by the doctors that this was definitely caused by the Moderna vaccine. It caused a transverse myelitis reaction, which I am still dealing with. My walking is extremely slow, and the sensation issues persist, along with incontinence.  I have all of my medical records and diagnosis for record.  The hope is this will eventually correct, but for now, I am still in PT/OT twice a week.
LAB_DATA: There are so many tests to list...I am happy to fax a copy. On the 8th, many tests were run including   Lumbar puncture- 3/8 MRI of cervical and thoracic spine- Brain MRI Abdominal CT on the 4th They tested for Lymes, MS, Autoimmune diseases, IGG, HIV, Neuromyelitis optica, etc.. All tests came back negative.  More details

SYMPTOM_TEXT: acute hemolytic anemia; she developed DIC; Hbg was 6.0; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician.  A 51-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) solution for injection, dose 1 via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified date (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as single dose for Covid-19 immunisation. Medical history included ongoing Wilson's disease, copper overload syndrome (taken Penicillamine for decades). Concomitant medication included ongoing penicillamine taken for Wilson's disease and copper overload syndrome. The patient was admitted to the hospital last week with a life-threatening illness. After multiple tests the physician believed it was related to patient's 1st dose of the vaccine. She had acute hemolytic anemia and her HBG was 6.0. The physician also stated patient developed DIC (disseminated intravascular coagulation). She was transfused with 3 units of blood due to adverse reactions and improved. She then received 2 more units of blood and was steadily improving. The patient has a history of Wilson's disease, copper overload syndrome, and has taken Penicillamene for decades, which can cause hemolysis. The patient was still taking this medication and was still getting better. This patient was due for her 2nd dose soon. The physician will defer to a later date. The physician would like to request if there was any information/data regarding hemolysis, DIC associated with the vaccine. The events were reported as life-threatening. Patient was admitted to hospital in Mar2021 due to the events. Multiple tests done in Mar2021 with unknown result. Outcome of the events was recovering.  Information on lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Due to a plausible drug-events temporal association, the company cannot completely exclude a contributory role of vaccine BNT162b2 administration in the development of the reported, serious events: "hemolytic anemia and disseminated intravascular coagulation, with HBG 6.0, as consequence of anemia.  The impacts of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.
